animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Gumdrop would like whoever is snoring to please stop. She's trying to sleep and its waking her up. Shhh! ! Don't tell her it's her. No one told this girl about a decompression period. She's made herself right at home with her new foster!

Gumdrop is a 3 year old heartworm negative female. She is one of the happiest dogs her foster Mom has met in a long time, despite obvious signs of past abuse. She loves meeting new people of all sizes and is very gentle with kids. She is housebroken and crate trained, walks on a leash like a champ and rides in the car like a proper lady! She is looking for a nice warm home full of love and belly rubs. She loves cuddling and taking couch naps. She is lower energy and greatly enjoys laying next to someone.

Gumdrop has visible hip dysplasia of the right hip and will undergo surgical correction in the next few weeks.

She does have great range of motion and mobility spite
how bad her hip looks.
She enjoys running in the yard, does stairs well, jumps up on the sofa just fine. But she is definitely in pain. When you touch that hip she turns into it and bumps your hand away. Even the lightest touch makes her wince. She's been started on some medications for pain and we anticipate a successful surgery.

She does well with all the resident dogs little and big and has meet some cats she likes.

If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description: Apache is a PACC return customer and a volunteer favorite. This handsome, friendly boy was originally brought to PACC for medical treatment after possibly being hit by a car. Apache has a happy, bubbly personality and loves his people friends. When meeting other dogs in PACC playgroup, Apache was most interested in being near the people in the yard. He needs to meet any resident dogs before heading home. Here is what a previous foster had to say about Apache: Apache has been a dream to foster! This handsome boy is a huge lover - he'll lean into you and fall right into your lap. Housetrained? Yes Details on training: Apache is very well-trained and obedient. He is fully crate trained and he sits very well. He sits when he waits for food, to be leashed up, and upon command. Affection level: Apache is VERY affectionate! He definitely takes comfort in staying near his people. He loves to snuggle and cuddle and will lean into you and fall directly into your lap. He's a 65-pound lap dog! Play behavior: Apache is so fun and loves to play with his toys! He loves all toys but especially Kongs and tennis balls. He is very playful and will play bow and wag his tail often when playing with you. He loves playing fetch! Apache LOVES water - more than any dog I've ever known! He is happiest when playing with/in water. Activity level: Very active! He has lots of energy and a fun-loving spirit. He also knows when to relax if you're busy and will snooze on the couch! Best adjectives to describe him: Adorable, loyal, sweet, affectionate, gentle, active, fun-loving, happy, obedient, well-trained.

animal.description:
Dasher (Dash) is a 10 month-old Yellow Labrador mix who came to us after being found in South Carolina.  This handsome boy is neutered and chipped.

Dash is a great young dog who will make a fantastic, loyal and loving addition for a lucky family!  He learns quickly, having already mastered "Sit" and "Down" and is working on "Stay".  He responds to his name and to the command "No".  He is crate trained at night and does a good job when left alone for short periods during the day.  He hasn't been left alone for any longer periods during his stay so far.  He is learning not to jump on his Foster Mom but hasn't had any issues with jumping on other family members or guests.

He loves a good treat, squeaky toys and bones. The resident 6 year-old and 12 year-old humans refer to him as "sweet" and that he "loves belly rubs".  He does very well with children and has not had any issues with them. He loves them so much.

He is currently staying with two resident dogs; a 7 year-old female Yellow Lab and a 2 year-old male Black Lab mix.  Dash likes to tussle with the male resident dog as he is familiar with our young dog.  We have had some meet and greets with other dogs and Dash does not have the best doggie manners yet. So we feel it would be best if Dash was an only dog.

After running around, playing with his toys or wrestling he is very happy to curl up next to someone and take a long nap.  

Dash would benefit from an active family or fenced yard with space for him to run and explore.  Over the last month he's developed quite a sweet and loving personality so we're sure he'll do great at a new home with the right family!

PLEASE NOTE:  While this Lab may not be available for adoption by the time you complete the adoption process, other great Labs are always finding their way into our Rescue. 

For more information on this Lab, please contact INFO@BROOKLINELABRESCUE.ORG.  

If you are interested in adopting this Lab or any other Lab from our Rescue, please visit our Web site, www.brooklinelabrescue.org, for more information on our adoption process. If you need additional information about the adoption process or whether you are in our coverage area, please send an e-mail to our Rescue at info@brooklinelabrescue.org

Even if you are not ready to adopt, you can still help us help our Labs!

Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue is a 501(c)3 non-profit volunteer organization funded entirely by donations. Donations are always needed to help with veterinary costs, transportation, and supplies for our dogs. For information on donating to BLRR please click here. Donations are accepted via PayPal or you can mail a check to: Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue, P.O. Box 638, Warrington, PA 18976-0638

animal.description:
Lola is a three year old, female Blue Healer/Catahoula mix with a gorgeous speckled coat.  She is a large family-friendly dog that would be perfect for anyone that enjoys an active lifestyle.  Outgoing and affectionate, Lola loves having fun and needs plenty of exercise.  Lola would not be happy if left alone in a crate all day.  She is very bright and needs activity to keep her mind busy.  If you are looking for a running or hiking partner, this is your dog.  Lola is a pretty good ball player too!  She has a blast playing tag outside with several other dogs here at the shelter.  Another dog in the home would be a welcome playmate and help to keep her entertained.  Of course, you can always consider adopting one of her play group pals.  Cats would not be a good fit as Lola has strong herding instincts.  Lola has lived in a home before and been around children.  She seems to be housebroken and will need a fenced in yard to keep her from wandering.  This sweet girl is well mannered and very easy to train.  If you are looking for a fun-loving pup to be your companion, Lola is anxious to meet you.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

animal.description:
HALEY is a happy little circus clown :-) She chases her tail, greets you with a big smile, and wants to play play play. All of this shows the true spirit this smart gorgeous red heeler girl has despite the horrific violent act performed on her. At 8 weeks old she was taken to the top of a two-story building and intentionally thrown to the ground. She has spent the last 3 months healing. She's done a super job and her friend Keanu was with her every step of the way! Her left front leg will most likely forever be a bit shorter due to all the fractures she suffered. Everything else has healed very nicely. She's runs around with her friends great and loves water too! :-)

We would love Haley and Keanu to be adopted together if you don't have another dog. If you do have another young playful male dog we will consider adopting them seperately. Keanu has been an inspiration for Haley, coaxing her to follow him and play gently during her healing process. Now they know each other very well and run around the yard chasing each other, Haley taking an occasional dip in the water trough. Keanu has his own sad past - as a puppy, he was placed in a sealed box and left on the side of the road until someone found him. So in a way, they've helped each other.

Her adoption fee includes her spaying, vaccine series, rabies, deworming, and microchip. She was born on a reservation we work with August 18, 2020.  

We have specific ADOPTION and COVID rules listed below.

Revised adoption policy
Due to Covid -19 pandemic and social distancing requirements, we've revised our adoption policy. 

First, please email (desertpawsnm@gmail.com) to inquire before you fill out the online application to see if the pet is still available. (Please do not call or text). We'll send you a link to the application.

We are unable to do multi-dog/cat meetgreets or adoption events at this time or bring multiple animals to your house to choose from, so please only inquire if you're serious about adopting this particular animal. If you're just shopping around with several shelters and rescues, please let us know this. 

If your application is approved (which "could" take up to one week) then we will contact you to set up a Zoom chat or ph call to answer questions/clarify anything and set up a day/time to bring the pet to you. 

Since we can't come into the home/yard due to Covid-19, we ask that you send us pics /video of your home/yard/living area/current pets. 

We will discuss with you about meeting your other pets. At the meeting/adoption at your house (outside) please wear a mask (as will we), keep to a properly distanced social distance and have hand sanitizer and your own leash.

We adopt locally to Central Abq, Santa Fe, Los Alamos and Rio Rancho. No out of area adoptions inquiries please. No young children for our adoptions please.

The animals are fostered and our foster families like to know their fosters are happy, healthy, and cared for during their lifetime. We appreciate staying in touch periodically (just a pic, holiday card, social media, pics/videos  etc will make our work worthwhile :-))

Our volunteers and adoption board are working diligently with an overload of inquiries since Covid to match families and forever pets. Our workload on the reservations has also increased. We're sorry, but if you email us with questions that are already answered here or fill out an application that does not fit the parameters of our procedures we will not be able to reply to you. Thank you for your understanding on this!

Thank you - we look forward to hearing from you and having another furbaby united with a furever family!

animal.description:
Bubba is a 3 year old male lab mix.   He has quite a story for being just 3 years old. 

He was found as a stray with an injured front leg.  He was very scared and reactive in the shelter.  But the folks there saw something in him that they knew he was a good dog.    

When he first came in he was very kennel reactive but when out of the kennel he was a different dog.    He plays with other dogs but can be a little possessive of his things. 

For a year while he was worked with, he carried around  a painful, non-functioning front leg.   A vet said his leg was savable but we found that not to be true and our vet said he was in great pain (likely contributing to his behavior).  So his leg was amputated and he has not missed a beat!

He also is reactive to men.   He has never bitten a soul but will growl.   So we think the best home for him is either a female home or one where the male is dog savvy  and will be patient with him. 

Bubba is a big goofy, happy boy!  He loves to play and he loves to ride in the car!
We promise if you meet him you will love him.

Bubba is fostered in Windham, CT and his adoption is $400.00

animal.description:
Jackson is a 10 year old male dachshund. He is a mix of cream and red, so he's a light red/golden color. He is a big boy at 17.5 lb. and is a tweenie or small standard.

Jackson is pretty laid back around the house and with people. He's content to follow his brother Riley's lead. He is the opposite of his brother in that he doesn't like walks all that much. He prefers to get his exercise playing with toys. He will punch this with both paws and loves the sound squeakers make. This senior boy and his brother think they are puppies and will bring a smile to your face as you watch them run around.

He hates riding in the car and will get anxiety. He would love a home where he can sleep in bed with his human. He's not overly cuddly but likes to be near people. Jackson would do best in a home where there are people around most of the time. 

He needs some continuing work on his potty training, although his fosters have begun (He was potty pad trained and is now learning to go outside). He would not do well in a home with young kids (but teens would be ok).

Could rambunctious Jackson and his goofy brother Riley be the perfect pair for you? Apply on our website to be considered:

https://www.portlanddachshundrescue.org/adoptionform

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Noel is a cute, 1 year and a half old Pit Bull mix. He will be joining us from California on January 10th. We will post more info as we get to know him.

Seattle Foster Update:

He's a bit barky at new people, especially men, but once he knows it's ok he's wiggly. Still hesitant with men but I'm trying to walk him with some friends and have passed the leash over for a mile or two and he seems to be gaining confidence there.

The yard part is no big deal, he will go outside to potty but he does not like to spend much time outside, especially if it's raining.

He's doesn't recognize his own body size, he crashes into stuff in the house but he's just a big sweet pup. He followed foster Kiera straight up the wooden stairs at our neighborhood playground, he loved it. He'll go over the agility jumps in my yard, I think he'd love something like that. And he loves walks.

Noel would do best in a home with a resident dog that is close to our equal in size due to his exuberance and lack of body and handler awareness.

Noel would thrive in a home that can promote training, leadership and structure.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California and will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated in a loving foster home in the greater Seattle area.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Sherry has arrived in VA and is beginning the journey to her best life. Sherry was rescued from a high kill shelter in TX initially assessed as unable to walk; she was diagnosed with a fractured pelvis and has now started bearing weight on all legs again, yay! She saw the vet here in VA shortly after she arrived for repeat x-rays and a treatment plan. Sherry is a lucky lady and with continued crate rest and pain management she will not need surgery! She also had a much needed spa day and looks like a brand new pup! She is very sweet, loves to lean in for love and will make the most amazing & stunning sidekick. She is very friendly to adults and children, dog and cat test TBD, but non-reactive to passing dogs while on leashed potty breaks and stands nose to nose with my female on opposite sides of the fence nicely. This girl never stops wagging her tail. Sherry takes treats nicely and allows you to touch her and her bowls while eating. She will need some training to refine her manners but she is totally worth it and I can't wait to see her full transformation. If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

animal.description:
Riley is a 12 year old long hair black dachshund who weighs 15 lbs. He is a former IVDD survivor who had surgery many years ago and had no issues with his back. In fact, he loves to walk! He walks twice a day and will remind you if you forget (he's the perfect exercise buddy). Riley and Jackson are still working on their outdoor potty training at their foster home. Previously they were allowed to go on a potty pad indoors, so this is a learning curve for them.

Riley has allergies and wasn't on any medication when he arrived. He has since started hypoallergenic prescription food and will likely need to continue his allergy medicine (so his forever home should be prepared for these additional costs). He does have some fatty tumors and growths that we will biopsy at the time of his dental.

This is one happy, silly and mischievous boy! He would love to sleep in bed with his human but will tolerate sleeping in your room in his crate/pen with his brother Jackson. Speaking of Jackson, he really loves his brother! They are most definitely a bonded pair who will be adopted out together.

Are you a experienced doxie home that is looking for a goofy, loving and slightly naughty pair to light up your life? These two have so much to offer- you would never know they are seniors based on how they act!

Application link (please copy and paste into your browser's address bar)

About our rescue
We are a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in foster homes throughout the area or in some cases in the south waiting to be transported north. We do not have a physical shelter. However, meet and greets are set up for approved applicants.

Our Adoption Process
Visit our website www.necoonhoundrescue.org for information about the Coonhound and Beagle breeds. Read ‘Is a Coonhound Right for You’. 
If you'd like to apply, our application is available at the link above. Once we review your application one of our Adoption Counselors will be in touch to review it with you. Once the phone interview is completed, we will check your vet reference as well as a personal reference and conduct a home visit.

Her person/people to love her unconditionally

She likes dogs just needs slow introduction since the attack

A terrific family dog for children above 10 years of age.  A terrific play buddy for an existing family dog.
Cat tested with no reaction.

Required:  Enclosed, fenced yard.
Requirement for Adoption:
1. Work from home, stay at home or part-time employment.  This dog is too young to be left alone unsupervised and kenneling for more than 2 hours is unacceptable.
2. Feed only top quality foods.  We are strict regarding our dog's nutritional needs.
3. Monthly heartworm prevention.

If you're looking for a dog that is laid back that is not Jack, since Jack is still   puppy in behavior, energy and curiosity.  This is a dog whose mind is always going, so a home that can offer stimulation is ideal to maintain his overall balance.  When we first received this stunningly handsome dog from a high-kill shelter, Jack would literally bounce off the walls. Why?  Because no one from his past had ever taken the responsible time to simply guide him on how to act.  Jack has come a long, long way with our simple and basic behavioral training.  He wants to learn!  He wants to be guided.  He wants to please.  

No ice to be broken when meeting other dogs.  Jack's innate demeanor welcomes all dogs and all dogs easily welcome him -- hands down.  He has the type of personality that melds with any person or furry friend.  Great on a leash and a perfect passenger in a car, Jack barks only when alerted and when indoors he is hush-hush quiet. He does not jump up on people.  He does not lift his leg.  He is not a face licker. 
A handsome dog, Jack will melt your heart with eyelashes that adorn his warm and sincere eyes.  Count on Jack to be the most loyal and devoted best friend.

Feed your dog to do more than survive.  Feed your dog to thrive.
There is no logical basis to back feeding your dog the same dog food bag after bag.  This alone causes the dog's digestive system to be dependent on one food.  Rotate manufacturers.   No one dog food has it all.  ** No one dog food can satisfy and dog's nutritional needs long term.**  A dog's biological need is variety.  Raw diet is a dog's natural diet.  Our dogs are fed partial dry commercial food after soaked in water to mitigate dehydration within the dog and a raw egg and raw beef or poultry on top.

Please be fully aware what you are feeding your dog.  Check out the reviews.  For example in your search bar: MY DOG FOOD and add the word "review":  MY DOG FOOD REVIEW and websites will avail themselves to assist you.

We cannot guarantee the breeds of any of our dogs. DNA tests are not fully accurate. The breeds as disclosed are a guestimate based on physical characteristics and behavioral traits.

animal.description:
Blondie is a loving 3 year old lab/boxer mix! 

Blondie was found wondering the streets of Houston, Tx. Her finder noticed she had a collar so she brought her to a local shelter to scan for a microchip. Blondie was very sweet, and willingly jumped in the car. She was tail wags the whole time! 
Shelter staff did find her past owners contact information, however when they called he said ""If I wanted this dog, she wouldn't be on the streets right now. Don't contact me again."" Poor Blondie does not deserve a cold hearted owner. We are on a mission to find Blondie the loving home she deserves. This girl is so sweet! 

From the foster: Blondie is a sweet sweet girl who will make a wonderful colorado adventure dog! She is so gentle and loving, and shy and timid at first! She seems to be happy snuggling on the couch or doing her own thing. She LOVES being outside! She is timid now and seems to come from a rough past, but is quickly building trust and coming more and more out of her shell and building confidence! Will some extra love and care, and learning that she is safe, Blondie will be embodying her doggie confidence in no time! She is a smart girl who know how to sit, shake, and come. She is pretty good on a leash and is fully crate trained and potty trained! She goes to the door when she has to go out. Because Blondie seems to LOVE being outside, she would do great in a home with a backyard to play!

Blondie making friends: 
https://youtu.be/FqHySSn34Zw

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

animal.description:
Aviana ACCT-A-82253

This little one is the sweetest, most snuggly and calm girl around!! Aviana walks perfect on a leash - no bunny chasing ever. She is a social butterfly to the extreme, who loves to greet everyone she meets with tail wags and a happy face. She is always up for belly rubs or butt scratches and is the best snuggle couch potato partner around! She definitely does not believe in personal space and is a 50 pound velcro lap dog for sure. Aviana loved the little kids she has met, though she is not a fan of smaller dogs or cats. So a home without smaller animals is best. She was non reactive to larger dogs on our walks. Aviana also loves to go for car rides, and prefers to be in the passenger seat :)

Interested in meeting this sweet girl? Email her foster mom at stantonchris@comcast.net

Intake Reason: Stray (APO Pickup)
Sex: Female 
Age: 4Y
Altered: no

Videos: 
Aviana and Wheezy dog meet -- https://youtu.be/gRidtWVyiCU

Medical Observation: 
1/10 (Per Vet)-- Bloody stool in kennel
1/8 (Vet Check) -- Lesions on carpus and tarsus appear to be pressure sores likely due to extended exposure to hard surfaces, suspect from being caged. They appear non-infectious but will likely remain unchanged in appearance. Patient presents with moderate periodontal disease (devitalized canines) and would benefit from dental surgery. Saliva staining likely secondary to allergies - food v. atopy. She appears nonpruritic at this time. Patient's friendly demeanor makes her a very good candidate for adoption. 
1/7 (Intake Exam) -- Underweight; sores and lesions all over body; pressure sores on forearms and hind legs; muscle wasting all over body; open lesions on paws; dirty ears; underbite

Behavior Observation: 
1/11 (Per Foster Staff)-- Details from dog meet - Aviana and Agatha were walking towards each other in the parking lot so we conducted a brief meet with them. Both dogs were very polite and tolerant, tails flagging, and took turns sniffing each other. The meet went very well and both Aviana and Agatha appear to be dog-friendly.
1/10 (Per Volunteer)-- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social. Does try to head butt out of the door
Leash Skills: Pulls Minimally On Leash. Very nice leash walker
Handleability: Tense/Allows all handling. Started off with some mild crouching when I tried to pet her. She overcame that quickly and was OK w/ most handling.
Tag: Engages in play
Toys: Accepts a trade. She got a little obsessed with a ball but easily traded for a treat. A little grabby with treats. I just tossed them.
Color Level: Gold
1/9 (Per Foster Staff) -- Dog approached handler as soon as she was greeted in kennel. Easy to leash and lead out of kennel. Very minimal pulling on leash - walks pretty much in pace with handler. Once in eval room, solicited attention from handler, sat for treats, engaged in tag, allowed all over handling and petting. Did get a little stiff when body was first pet, but loosened up and leaned into the pets. Very social and followed handler around. Very easy to return to kennel. Enjoys treats!
1/8 (Per Vet) -- very friendly and affectionate; seeks attention; tolerates handling and examination 
1/8 (Per Lifesaving) -- During dog meet with Wheezy, Aviana seemed fine with Wheezy up until Wheezy tried to mount Aviana (See video "Aviana and Wheezy dog meet")
1/7 (Per Staff) -- Super super sweet docile friendly as can be young lady.. Leashes up no issue walks well on leash allows all handling let me pick her up.. Loves to give kisses and won't stop she's a big lap dog

animal.description:
Oberon “Oby” is a 10 year old male Yorkshire Terrier rescued as a surrender. His owner passed away and his family was unable to care for him.
Oby is just shy of 5 lbs and would do best in a quiet home where he can snuggle. He has no teeth but he’s a great eater of very small kibble mixed with a little bit of soft canned food. Very sweet boy who wants all the attention from his person. 

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA if it’s the best fit for the dog.

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

Roark is an active boy, so he would certainly enjoy an active family life and time to be outdoors each day to stretch his legs before cuddling up close to his favorite humans. Curious and watchful, Roark keeps track of the volunteers during play time to make sure he gets his share of love and ear scratching. Roark would equally love a canine sibling as he would be your one and only. Don't miss out on this fun-loving boy!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Name: Bronson

DOB: 10/24/2017

Weight: 80 Pounds

Adoption Fee: 375.00

*Currently receiving veterinary care in St. Cloud - he will need continued follow up appointments and any applicant should be prepared to drive to St. Cloud*

Bronson is a 3-year-old loving dog with advanced hip dysplasia looking for a FTA (Foster to Adopt home). Ruff Start is currently exploring options for long-term care and will likely need to fundraise before any major treatments. No matter what treatment Bronson receives, he should be on fish oils, anti-inflammatories (carprofen) and veterinary formulated joint supplements daily for the rest of his life, so his people will need to be prepared to take him to appointments and provide him his medications, currently twice daily. A home with fewer flights of stairs may also be beneficial, but would depend on the treatment decisions. Currently, Bronson is on pain medications and does well on the stairs most of the time, but at 80 pounds, help could be tough to provide as he gets older. He also has accidents in the house and wears a belly-band to help. He seems to do fine for a few days, then have a really bad day with multiple accidents. His signals are subtle, but I'd bet he would do well with bell-training as he is a fast learner and wants to please his people.

Bronson is a loving dog who loves to lay in bed and do his adorable wiggle-bite routine where he lays on his back and throws his head and butt around, wiggling while biting the air and smiling. Bronson gives lots of side-eye. If you talk about him: side-eye, look at him: side-eye, give him a direction: side-eye. He is goofy and silly, always making his fosters laugh. He has done extremely well with all visitors, dogs, and humans, and met some kids around 6-8 years-old on the street and did well, though he hasn't met any in the home. I have no concerns with him meeting any dogs or children; he has not had any cat intros and does loose his mind when he sees squirrels so he might not be ideal for a home with cats, but may be fine with slow intros and a dog-savvy cat. He can be vocal when he sees squirrels or other dogs from a window, though he is learning that we don't like barking and is starting to learn "go chill" when he gets too excited, which means he has to walk away from the door and go somewhere else, usually our bedroom, his safe-space, for awhile. Bronson does need to be fed separately from other animals - he likes to keep all his food for himself!

We have been teaching Bronson fetch. He is learning to play, but clearly never had the chance to play in his old life. We had another foster for a few weeks who helpfully taught Bronson to play with toys with other dogs and he is starting to try playing on his own. He has some hoarding tendencies that lead him to giving anyone who has a toy side-eye. He then walks over and VERRRY gently takes the toy, walks away, and puts it away for you. He will then gather all his toys and put them in his pile. He does not guard the pile and you can stick your hand in and take things out of it for him to remove and return. He is actually a pretty good organizer. Before the world froze over, we discovered that Bronson does want to bury bones in the yard and may dig a bit. He loves chewy bones, but not those fake bone things- those are for the toy pile.

Bronson is a food motivated learner. He knows "sit", "lay down" (when he feels like it and only after sitting), "leave it", "go bed", "ugh-ugh" (no), and "out" and is working on "look" for times he is distracted out walking. Bronson really wants to play with other dogs and gets very excited when he sees them. His gentle leader gives us lots of control and he is doing great, rarely even barking anymore, though he will cry the entire walk after seeing or hearing another dog. He just wants to love everyone. After a few months with Bronson, I am very confident in his ability to adapt and do well in a loving home. The only time he ever gets upset by anything is if his back legs get caught on something while moving around or after he plays too much with another dog and is hurting. Even then, being upset means he might cry and give you side-eye or mope a bit- he is a very sensitive boy who wants a home where he can live with lots of love (and food!) and comfort, get all the pets and bones, and maybe even have another dog to hang with- no puppies though! Puppies have too much energy and hurt his poor hips.

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal. Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals! All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs). Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept. Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet LLOYD, see the contact information below.

Lloyd is a handsome neutered male Belgian Malinois. His coloring is called fawn. He is 7 years old and weighs a bit over 85 lbs. This boy came to the county shelter as an underweight stray who had bad skin and an untreated injury to one of his front legs. The shelter x-ray’d his leg and found an old injury that causes a bit of a hitch in his step. But it doesn’t slow him down! A little Rimadyl seems to be just what he needs.

Lloyd has a rough style of play, so if he goes to a home with another dog, they should be large, energetic breeds who can match his playfulness. If you have kids, they would need to be older if they will be playing with Lloyd.

He is up to date on all of his vaccinations and wants to find his forever home. If you want to meet Lloyd, you will need to schedule an appointment. Call the San Diego County Department of Animal Services – South Region at 619.767.2675 and be sure to have his ID information available: ID#: A1879628; Tag#: S213.

Did you know you can sponsor a pet on the ARRF Petfinder site? When you click an animal's information, there is a box in the upper-righthand corner where you can ask about the pet, mark it as a favorite, or select "Sponsor" or "Share." It's a great way to help with just the click of a button!

animal.description: Meet Tank! This shy guy found himself with us due to no fault of his own. His family had to move to the west coast due to military orders. Unfortunately they were not able to Tank with them. Tank is a very sweet boy. Once he gets to know you his true colors will shine through. In the world we live in today, we do not blame him for taking his time when letting people into his circle of trust. Tank did previously live with children but due to the fact that he can be a bit of a nervous nelly at first, all children in the home should be 12 years and older. He has also lived other dogs. If you have a mild mannered pup or two that wouldn't mind a new friend that would be great. Tank is crate, leash and potty trained. He is treat motivated, taking treats very nicely. He already knows sit, down, stay, come and paw. If you have time to get to know Tank and you can afford him the time to blossom into the loving pup we all know then ask to meet Tank today.

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Meet Biggie! This big, sweet, 1 year old boy is looking for a new home to call his own! He was turned over to the shelter by his owner on 1/09. The owner said he traveled too much; his family did not like Biggie and wanted him gone as well. Biggie is good with the kids and house trained. The owner, who has had this sweet, 57 pound boy since he was 4 weeks old, said that Biggie has not been around other pets, but also said Biggie needed to be an only pet. Biggie and his adorable smile have so much love and joy still to give! With a little TLC, bonding time, and plenty of playtime, Biggie will become a wonderful and loving member of the family! Get to know and love this sweetheart in run 881. His ID number is 626789. Biggie is up-to-date on vaccines, now neutered, and will be microchipped, and heartworm tested upon adoption. Biggie can't wait to start loving his new family!

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description:
Holly is a beautiful, playful, sweet ball of fur!  This puppy chow is 7.5 months old and 30 lbs. and estimated birthday of June 4, 2020. She is crate trained, house broken, and loves to play with the other chows. Holly follows her foster mom around everywhere and likes to be petted and loved. She is timid and shy at first but warms up to and bonds better with women at first. She is getting better with men and older children as she socializes more.  

Please consider adding this puppy chow to your chow experienced home!  Prefer to adopt locally or within driving distance to St. Louis to a female or couple who are home often and have another playful dog.  Fenced yard required for zoomies.  Bonus and discount if you can also adopt Holly’s best friend Maci. 

The adoption fee is $350 and includes a general vet exam, heartworm testing and/or treatment (as necessary), spay/neuter surgery, shots, microchip, worming, grooming and foster care. Experienced chow ownership and credible vet references are required.

If you meet this criteria, please email to set up a meet and greet, request an adoption application to fill out and return to us. If it is a good fit, then we will have a home visit done. Then pay the adoption fee and pick up your new fur baby!  

Please email deniserahjes@aol.com or woof3x@swbell.net for more information.  Thanks!

This is a courtesy post.  If interested in Zeus, please contact Tamra DeMartini at
760-715-4703 cell


Zeus  is around 2-3 yo,  60 pound neutered male. He was rescued him from the shelter a few months ago. Didnt do well at the shelter—wouldn’t look up at me, very sad, etc.  Seems to be friendly toward dogs. I’d say bigger and submissive dogs. Most likely females would be ok. Better yet, only dog. He LOVES to run. He can outrun even my son who’s in the military & runs a lot. Does have a prey drive....wants the bunnies on walks pretty badly. He’s very friendly and loves people. But about 60 lbs so no small kids. He needs someone who realizes he needs exercise, a good sized yard and is firm. He also Loves to cuddle on the couch (thinks he’s a lap dog ?). Great in the car. Housebroken. Will run tho if you leave a door open....thinks that’s a big game so he needs a secure yard and home.

I can be reached if you have any other questions thru email or more preferably text/call.

Tamra DeMartini
760-715-4703 cell

You can complete an adoption application on our website at:  
     www.onceuponatailrescue.com
or
     Scroll down on this page & click "More About Us", & then click "Adoption            Application" underneath our bright Pink logo. 

If you want to meet a pup in person, Once Upon a Tail Rescue does adoption events at PetSmart in Covington, LA on most Saturdays with many of our adoptable dogs there. 

Don't forget to complete your application ahead of time, so you don't miss out on the pup you've connected with.  If pre-approved, you have first priority & can usually take home your new best friend the same day!  

*Please note that there is no obligation to adopt by completing an application.*

**All dogs are required to have complete vet services, including shots, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip, which are included in the Adoption Fee. If you wish to utilize a different veterinarian for rabies vaccination and/or spay or neuter, the adoption fee is still the same but the adopter is responsible for the vaccination and spay/neuter fees. There will also be a refundable deposit required. The deposit will consist of a $10 rabies vaccination waiver deposit will consist of a $25 spay/neuter waiver deposit. City license fees are not included in this price. All dogs and cats residing in Bedford Texas are required to have a city license.



ALL ADOPTED ANIMALS MUST BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED AND RABIES VACCNATIED WITHIN A SPECIFIED TIME OR CITATIONS WILL BE ISSUED TO THE ADOPTER. 



Bedford residents must also purchase a $5 city license.  All other vaccinations and health services are the adopter's responsibility.  Not all animals that are currently available for adoption are listed on the webpage, so please visit the shelter to see every animal that is in need of a new home.  Animals may be viewed anytime during our regular hours which are 11-6 Monday through Friday and 11-2 on Saturdays.  Animals cannot be placed on hold for potential adopters and all adoptions are first-come, first-serve.

animal.description:
Beya is 5 years old and about 10 lbs. Almost all black chihuahua mix. She comes to us from Tijuana and knows Spanish.
She is a very loving, well behaved, and calm girl. She does a happy wiggle when she sees her people! She also gets along well with other dogs.
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

home page.

animal.description:
Don't judge a book by it's cover and definitely don't judge Alfred by his legs! 

Alfred was an owner surrender due to the owner not being able to afford to feed or care for him. Alfred appears to have suffered injuries to both of his left legs due to a car accident. He did not receive vet care and they healed poorly. His legs do not seem to bother him or slow him down. He runs and jumps like any other dog. Alfred had waited in the shelter for a really long time, when PAWS gave him a chance. He does need his legs wiped down after bathroom breaks as he has the tendency to accidentally get them dirty when going the bathroom. 

He is the happiest dog and has plenty of energy to play and run. He is great with other dogs and loves to be around humans. He would do well with a large yard to burn some energy in or someone who will take him for good walks or a run. He is crate trained and sleeps in the crate all night without an accident! He is also mostly house trained. 

Alfred would do best in a home with an active lifestyle! A home with small children may not be a good fit, as he has energy and likes to jump. He needs a home where his humans can give him the time to exercise and burn energy. He is well mannered once he gets his initial energy out. He is still young and would love to have a yard to play in. Alfred loves other dogs and would do best with a home with other dogs. He loves to play! Alfred pulls on the leash some but responds well to correction. When on walks he does demonstrate some fear of cars- which makes sense with his leg issues. He will need a family committed to giving him basic obedience training and he will flourish. 

He's a goofy boy - see here - https://youtu.be/CXoov0ZZQZs

Name: Alfred Major
Breed: Hound Mix
Sex: Male
Age: 2 years
Weight: 45 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Neg
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Older children only due to his energy level and tendency to jump up.
Good with Dogs: Yes- loves other dogs! 
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Looking for a laid back, super sweet girl to welcome into your home? Well, Sabine is looking to move into her retirement years with a quiet family or couple. She has excellent house manners, and her potty training days are long behind her. A large, fenced yard, or perhaps a farm, would be like heaven on earth for this older gal to roam and sniff out all there is to sniff. She will follow her nose to her heart's content. Sabine is around 5 years old and about 73 pounds. She isn't needy as far as seeking out attention but if you give it, you will get it right back with a happy tail wag and a chin in your lap. Since Sabine likes to roam, a leisurely walk around the neighborhood would be enjoyable for her. She would love to snooze at your feet or in front of the fire while you chill on the couch. Sabine gets along with her four-legged friends and loves belly rubs from her two-legged ones. She may even join you up there!
If you're searching for a loving, low-key, and loyal companion come
meet Sabine and be prepared to fall in love.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Kit Kat is in a foster home, and is currently not at the shelter. Please find info below on how to adopt her, thanks.



**Check out my Facebook page - www.facebook.com/maria.braganza.1 **



Hi, I'm Kit Kat, and I'd like to be your new best friend. I'm a curious, alert, attentive, young dog ready to experience each day to the fullest! In the morning, I enjoy a good stretch and thumping my tail, before going out for a walk. During the day, I love to spend as much time near you as possible. If you're willing to play with me, even better: I love to play fetch and with squeaky toys, or a good chewy bone can keep me busy for a while. When I tire, I'll take a good nap before I'm ready for more action! My foster family has occasionally left me home alone between 2-8 hours and it's gone well, but if you work outside the home be aware that I'll be eager for lots of attention when you come back. I'm good in my crate at night and in the car when we go for rides. 



I am looking for a family interested in training me to be all that I can be. My foster mom would be happy to tell you about all our training together. I need an adult-only home where I'm the only kid around - animal or human - (but who could want more?). Given that other dogs aren't my thing, I'd prefer a home with its own entrance, no apartment buildings please. A bonus would be a safely fenced yard where I can run and run to my heart's content! My foster mom says I have a heart of gold and eyes to match! She's happy to tell you lots more about me.



HOW TO ADOPT - Please fill out a Dog Adoption Application, available at http://www.seattle.gov/animalshelter/forms.htm and email it to the Seattle Animal Shelter Foster Dog Program at adoptionreview@gmail.com.



IMPORTANT NOTE: Many of our dogs will receive numerous applications, and the Seattle Animal Shelter asks for your patience during the process of finding the very best match. If you have questions about this dog that have not been answered above, please contact us at sasfosterdogs@gmail.com. If you would like to arrange to meet this dog, you must submit an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
Lily is in a foster home, and is currently not at the shelter. Please find info below on how to adopt her, thanks. 



Meet Lily the Wonder Dog. On my foster mom's Instagram page I'm known as Lily the Llama Unicorn Slayer because I'm a huge fan of cuddling AND destroying stuffed animals. Also a huge fan of Frisbees, playing ball, burrowing into wool and fleece blankets, long brisk walks, and people. I've been told that I'm wickedly smart and graceful at home. Once settled, I am an affectionate dog who loves to spend my days cuddling with my people, sleeping, playing, training, eating, long walks, running through puddles and in the rain.



What my friends at Seattle Animal Shelter say about me:

	I am a good girl who gets nervous around other dogs.

	Once in a home and away from other dogs, I am able to relax and show my true personality. 

	Get to know me. Watch my video.

	I need a safe home without other dogs. I can hear them but if I see them I get uncomfortable and will start barking to make them go away. 

	If you are a human, I love you instantly and want to show you love. 

	I am house and crate trained (and use my crate when the vacuum is running). 

	I am very smart and active. I will need a family ready to establish a routine full of fun physical and mental activities.



The type of home I am looking for:

	I need to be the only pet in the home (no cats, small animals, or other dogs).

	I will need a yard with a secure 6 ft. privacy fence to run and zoom around. Currently, I am walking with my foster around 5 miles/day and loving it! 

	When we get home, we'll play tug, destroy my stuffy, and/or ball. It takes a lot to tire me out but it is fun to play with me. If my family has more than one person, y' all could take turns. 

	My reactivity makes it difficult to be near other animals, so I cannot live in apartment buildings or other densely populated areas. 

	When out on a walk I need a person who will stay attentive while I am sniffing my way down the street and who has the ability to help me stay safe and calm down if we run into another dog. I am not being a jerk. I am just scared and need your help to be the best dog that I can be. 



Health and Behavior Considerations:

On walks, Lily reacts to other dogs by barking and lunging ("reactivity"). She's easily directed but needs someone who has experience with dogs. She is 67lbs and needs a family who is ready to give her the time and extra training she needs. She's a great dog who loves her people completely and wants to be a good girl. She will need jobs that uses her smarts or she will get bored and frustrated. She's graceful in the house and loves to snuggle. 



HOW TO ADOPT - Please fill out a Dog Adoption Application, available at http://www.seattle.gov/animalshelter/forms.htm and email it to the Seattle Animal Shelter Foster Dog Program at adoptionreview@gmail.com.



IMPORTANT NOTE: Many of our dogs will receive numerous applications, and the Seattle Animal Shelter asks for your patience during the process of finding the very best match. If you have questions about this dog that have not been answered above, please contact us at sasfosterdogs@gmail.com. If you would like to arrange to meet this dog, you must submit an adoption application. Thank you!

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Murphy is very good natured and has managed to get all three of my dogs to play with him. He is friendly to all people and loves to meet new people. Before being rescued, I don't think he had been taught any manners but he learns very fast. He wants to please and he enjoys people very much.

Murphy loves to play. He is just a youngster at around 1 year old. He weighs about 72 pounds. He is house trained and crate trained. Older children would be a better fit for him due to his enthusiasm. Murphy would not be good in a home with cats. 

Murphy can be a bit too friendly to new people and will jump sometimes. He has learned not to jump up on us and I believe with continued training he will learn quickly to meet people politely. 

He has not chewed up anything inappropriate but he does like to drag clothes or blankets around. He enjoys chewing bones and we keep a lot around and I think it helps keep him from chewing the wrong things. 

He does well in his crate if I put a kong stuffed or something in the crate with him. He sleeps quietly through the night. He should be crated when left alone.

Murphy is looking for an active home. He loves people and truly wants to please. He is an athletic dog who would love going for daily runs - he is good on a leash but he does love to chase squirrels and any other small critter he might see.

Murphy will make a wonderful addition to the right family. He needs someone committed to daily exercise and continued training. He has only been with us a short while but has learned so much about proper behavior. He wants to please and is very treat motivated. He has a big heart and is so good natured. He gets along with my dogs beautifully. I think he probably needs another playful dog in the home as well.

If you are interested in Murphy and are an approved adopter, please contact your Adoption Coordinator to be added to Murphy’s list. If you are not yet approved you can find our adoption guidelines and application at:  www.savealabrescue.org

Murphy is fostered in RI

animal.description:
Pignoli is a 3 year old, brown & white male pittie mix weighing in around 60 lbs. Pignoli has been known as a vivacious pittie who loves to snuggle on your lap. Pignoli was brought into our local shelter as a stray in Chicago. He is a quick learner with a happy personality who loves to play with toys and eat, eat, eat!

Pignoli is good with other dogs and small children. He really likes to engage with dogs to play and run; he is still learning to listen to other dogs and learn from them. He is great with younger children, but is learning his manners around them to not jump! He calms down quickly and enjoys being around kids.

Pignoli is crate trained and learning that it is a safe place to be in. Overall, he is a great companion! He is still learning some commands but so far has mastered ‘sit’, ‘paw’, and ‘down’. He would thrive in an active household, but enjoys snuggling on your lap as well! He is good in the car and will work for food or treats!

Visit www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey today to apply for and meet Pignoli!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Cremi! I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I like to play with other small dogs like myself but I do think that I would prefer to be in an adult-only home. I struggle to feel comfortable around people and am often very timid and scared. When I'm scared, I often like to spend my time in a small and enclosed space to help make me feel better. I may even be able to live happily with a feline companion. I'd benefit most from an experienced dog owner who can help me learn to come out of my shell a little bit and I would be perfect for apartment living, as I am quite small and don't require a large open space to run around in. I can be fearful of loud noises and sudden movements and sometimes when I'm really afraid, I don't have much of an appetite. I think I'd be happiest living in a quieter home environment, but I do love to receive visitors and will always welcome them with a wagging tail. I may even be the type of pup that you can bring out and about with you on your daily activities! I do appear to have some training, but could still use some additional work, particularly as it relates to potty-training. I'm learning to love to go on leashed walks here at the ranch but my absolute favorite activity is always going to be snuggling up on the couch next to you!

animal.description: Rex is a sweet young guy who has been at PACC before and sadly finds himself here again. Rex was housetrained and in a former home and slept in bed with the kids or in his own cozy dog bed. While Rex is a lover of people, he's a little selective when it comes to other dogs. For that reason, we recommend an only dog home and that Rex not visit dog parks. Rex is easy to leash up and loves to be petted all over. Rex's former owners say that he was a great addition to their family. If you're looking to expand your family, make an appointment today to meet Rex! Today was my first time walking Rex- he was very excited to get out! We exited the kennel and Rex settled into a loose leash walk and seemed to enjoy exploring his surroundings. We walked to the grassy field and saw several dogs go by. Rex watched them with interest but with relaxed body language. He knows sit, and took chicken treats gently. He was enjoyed me petting him when we sat briefly in the park. - PACC volunteer Text Rex' volunteer advocate, Ursula, about him: 520-743-0280 REX IS ENROLLED IN THE GOOD DOG PROJECT AT PACC - Read a message from his case manager here: tinyurl.com/gdpmessage - Ask his case manager about him: rachel.jones@pima.gov

animal.description: Hi! My name is Cinder and I have a special talent. I can tell you something about myself with every letter of my name! How cool is that? Ready? C is for caring. I may act goofy at times but I am pretty smart about where you hide those treats. N is for naps! If you call my name, I might not hear it because I am taking a nap. D is for dog. I mean that is what I am. A special dog in fact. E is for enthusiastic! Anything can make me excited. From treats to a walk in the park, I make sure to take lifes simple pleasures to the max. And R is for running. That is how I keep my body in great shape. Hope to meet you soon!

animal.description: If interested in adopting a pet from our shelter you will need to fill out a request to adopt. There will be a overnight wait to get this approved. Adoption fee for puppies or purebred dogs (no papers) is $100.  If not spayed or neutered, a deposit is required. The deposit is $130 for dogs and $55 for cats. Your deposit is returned after the animal is spayed/neutered. All animals adopted from the shelter MUST be spayed/neutered. Dogs arriving at the shelter receive DA2PP and Bordetella. Cats receive a vaccine for Rhinotracheitis-Calici-Panleukopenia-Chlamydia Psittaci. The animals at our shelter have been picked up stray. Please remember this when requesting additional information about the animals. Questions can be emailed to emporiakansasanimalshelter@gmail.com

animal.description:
Tater is a 2 1/2 month old cattle dog mix.  He has been in foster care in Louisiana since he was 2-3 days of age.  He will be joining us at AHR on January 30th, along with his siblings Mr. B and Hazel.  

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
*Ready for Adoption*

Frost is a sweet and mellow 9 year old Chihuahua! He does have cataracts in both eyes and is blind, he is also deaf, but it doesn't stop him one bit! He came to TNT after he and 4 other chihuahuas were found in their deceased owners home. They all had very bad flea dermatitis, ear infections, and just poorly cared for. After coming to us, he has had all medical needs taken care of. Frost has had 11 infected teeth removed, been neutered, received antibiotics for his skin, and is starting feel and look much healthier! 
 His schedule consists of: Eat, sleep, snuggle, repeat. He's happiest with his human, especially males.  He will need slower paced home with a family that will shower him with cuddles and belly rubs. He doesn't wander off but does get lost easily, and with being blind & deaf, a fenced in yard is required. Having another senior dog in his future home to keep him company when the humans aren't isn't a must, but we are sure he would love it!

 He's just as sweet as can be, even with all his issues. His tail wags as soon as he realized you are near, and can't wait to snuggle. He is a major cuddle bug that deserves a home that will give him all the cuddles he wants! Frost's adoption fee is $300.

Meet Harvey, a Lab mix who weighs about 85 lbs. He is sweet, friendly and is considered a medium-high energy dog who loves to play fetch! He also knows basic commands such as; sit, down, off, paw and stay. He should be the only animal in the home and will need some training on his guarding behavior. Harvey would do best without kids, and not in an apartment setting. You can also watch for stories, pictures and videos about Harvey on our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/

 Adoption fee: $350

Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.

All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.

Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
