animal.description:
Charlie - a classic name for a classic companion. Charlie is a gorgeous 18 month old medium-sized German Shepherd mix (his DNA test says he also has Australian Cattle Dog and Dachshund among several other breeds!) who originally came to CCR from a shelter in Texas. Charlie was adopted and well loved, but unfortunately his adopter didn't feel he would be the right dog for his lifestyle after quarantine ended. Now he's back and looking for the exact right fit! Charlie can take a minute to cut loose in new environments, but if you give him a minute to observe and adjust at his own pace, he'll love you as much as he's ever loved anyone! Then he's a goofy, athletic, affectionate dog who loves to go for long walks, runs, and then snuggle on the couch. He loves belly rubs, snuggles, and lots of praise - this guy is a ham for your attention! Charlie is good with other dogs off leash at daycare and the dog park, though he prefers the company of his people at home even more. Because he's a little high-strung, Charlie will thrive with a confident, easygoing handler who makes him feel safe and lets him fly his fun flag! Charlie is looking for adult only homes, and he respectfully requests no kitties please.

To meet Charlie, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org!

animal.description:
Sly...that's how he sneaks into your heart! This boy is the absolute definition of "don't judge a book by its cover" - though he starts off terrified, he soon reveals the goofy pup underneath! Sly is an 11 month old retriever mutt who came to CCR with his brother from a shelter in Arkansas. Unfortunately, Sly was done a huge disservice in Arkansas - he was kept from 1 month old to 9 months old in a rural shelter with only his brother, receiving very little of the socialization young puppies need to feel safe in the world. Because of that, Sly has been initially freaked out by all of the things that a normal dog should be comfortable with. The good news is that Sly is a friendly, playful, goofy boy - you just have to give him time to adjust. He's been living happily in foster care where his foster parents have seen first hand how a super petrified dog can bloom into a nutty teenage puppy who loves to play play play! Sly will likely always be a slow adjuster to new things, but he's grown leaps and bounds in his confidence and bravery. His new home will need to continue working on exposing him slowly to new things, but if the past two months are any indication - slow and steady wins the race for Sly! When he's comfortable, he's all knucklehead - he can jump high, run fast, and he LOVES to play with toys! Sly loves other dogs and may do well with a dog friend, though he does have trouble sharing his special things with other dogs in the home (especially his toys). That's likely because he grew up competing with his brother for everything. Sly has no guarding issues with people, though. He'll do best in a home that has access to a fenced yard while he adapts to a new environment, and to a home that is happy to be more routine-oriented and predictable while Sly adapts. For now, older kids 12 and up and adults are preferred. Sly may do fine with cats since he's skittish and open to learning new things!

To meet Sly, please submit an application at chicagocaninerescue.org!

animal.description: Valora, a sweet, energetic 2-3 year old female pit bull mix, suffered injuries after a witness reported her being thrown from an overpass.  We have been nursing her back to health with wound care and TLC, and while she has a weakly functioning foreleg as a result of the incident, the veterinarian expects rest will help her to recover and regain use of that leg, with surgery being a distant possibility .  Despite a hefty bump on her noggin, a bum foreleg that is on the mend, and testing positive for heartworms, she smiles always and shows no signs of any of her issues keeping her down!  She can run as fast, jump as high and chase all the balls as if she had all four good legs, so once she regains full use of her leg, she will be full speed ahead!  If Valora has captured your heart, we feel she would do best in a home with older children who can keep up with her energy level, and a fence would be a definite plus!  Give us a shout at 979-337-7351 and we can schedule a meet and greet to give this deserving girl a second chance at a good life.

animal.description:
Say Hello to Scout! This handsome dude is a 3 year old Golden Retriever Mix who weighs about 65lbs.  Scout is a friendly guy and would love to be the center of your world.  He likes other dogs with slow introductions but really doesn't want to share his stuff, so he would prefer to be an only pet in the home.  He would also do best with older children & no cats since fast movements aren't his favorite thing.  Scout loves being outside and enjoys attention.  He would prefer to be with his people all the time, but doesn't need to be crated when left alone.  Scout needs an experienced dog owner, who will be his leader.  If Scout sounds like a good fit, apply today!  His adoption fee is $250.00.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description: Hi, I'm Cedric. I'm a snuggly, super-handsome, neutered 5 year old lab mix who reminds my foster family of a baby polar bear. I weigh 48 lbs, and I was brought to the Humane Society of Central Texas as a stray who was very scared in the shelter. I'm crate trained and doing well working on my potty manners in the house with occasional accidents. I'm dog friendly, gentle and kid friendly, and I love to be near my people. Since I'm not a puppy, I don't get into much trouble with chewing or destructive behaviors, and I'm a good boy who sleeps all night. I love to go for walks and runs, play outside with toys or puppy wrestle with the other dog in my foster home, but I'm also content to lay around and cuddle for most of the day as long as I get some exercise. I must have been mistreated sometime in my past, because I'm still very fearful of most men until I get to know them and often cower or growl at sudden movements or things that catch me off guard. I might be a great fit for a home with a single mom or a young women that would enjoy having a loyal, loving companion that could intimidate strangers with my growl or bark- even though I'm really just a big baby. If you're interested in giving me a home where I can continue to overcome my fears in a loving, secure place, let's set up a meet and greet!

animal.description: From his ofster Alfie is a beautiful white bully mix who has eyes that look right into your soul. While Alfie does all the normal dog things like chasing his tail, running zoomies in the yard, working for treats (and so much more) there is one thing that makes him a little more special. Alfie is deaf and he is working really hard on communicating with us utilizing our hands. Although I am convinced he loves to be talked to, so I talk to him. Alfie is young, maybe 2 years old and about 60lbs. He is athletic but he also loves to cuddle with you on the couch. He is housed trained, walks well on a leash, does a great job at watching you and looking at you for direction. We are working on being able to be in a crate and building up that duration. We are also working on being able to leave him in a safe space while we are at work and he is doing great! He is currently living with a dog savy cat. Alfie has never shown that he is going to hurt our cat however he really wants to play with her and struggles with understanding that her claws mean no. He just needs some redirection or a cat who isn't 18yrs old and wants to play with him. Alfie may be deaf, but he lives just like a hearing dog except you have to communicate with your hands and ensure he is looking at you. Training may take a little more persistence than a hearing dog but he still learns the same way. Due to the ability of being startled/surprised, he is recommend with older children. Alfie is also nervous outside of his safe space (home) with people he doesn't know. He needs a strong leader who has experience that he can count on to keep him safe and continue to build his confidence.

Please only apply if you are serious about adopting as placing each foster dog in the best home takes time and effort by our volunteers.

animal.description:
Winter is a small 8 year old 25 pound beagle. She came into a rural shelter as a stray. She was scared at the shelter so we took her in.

Winter really likes people. She will follow you around the house and sit near you on the couch. She is good with other dogs and cats. She is very sweet and loves to be petted. She is startled by loud noises and when walking outside on a leash she is afraid of young children, so she would do best in a home with no small children under 10.

When Winter arrived she did have several masses that were removed, but they were not cancerous. She has been spayed, she is up to date on shots, micro-chipped and negative for heartworm.

She is housebroken. She would do great in a house with another dog but if someone was home most of the day she would be fine as the only dog. She would prefer a fenced yard so she can go out and sniff like all beagles love to do.

Winter is located in Williamsburg, Va. For an application go to www.homesfurhounds.com.

animal.description:
*Please read the entire bio before submitting an application. This girl will require an experienced dog owner and HAS to have another dog in the home.*

Let me reintroduce myself. I am Doris, but my foster momma calls me Dori. You see, I was up for adoption over 3 months ago, but I was a bit of a wild child. I'm still skittish and unsure about all the pets and humans. I'll require a very patient human that will let me come out of my shell on my own time. 

I have the softest fur now that you'll ever touch. I'm really a sweet girl and love to run on the grass in the park. I love going on walks, soft beds, tasty food and follow my foster momma everywhere. Oh and don't forget my foster mom's doggy children, they've really been teaching me how to dog. I would make the greatest companion as I really don't like to be alone. Will you be the one to show me that this world isn't as scary as I think?

Notes from her foster mom:
Dori is a very special pup that will require someone VERY patient, no young kids, chasing her in any way freaks her out. She's still very much learning the world and to trust. Dori NEEDS to be in a home with a calm, sweet and playful dog. She's learning how to play with toys and other dogs, and she gets her confidence from other dogs. She's house trained, she'll go out on her own (if you open the door) in the backyard and come back in. She definitely CANNOT be left unattended until trustworthy outside though. She's not fond of crates, but will stay if needed. She sleeps quietly through the night in her bed next to ours. She's really a little shadow and does not like being left alone. P.S. the hair on her leg will grow back, it's from having a short visit to ER. 

Dori is a Yorkie/Poodle mix that we estimate to be around 4 yrs old. She's about 7.5 pounds.

animal.description:
Polly - 5-6 years old. Needs a home with a yard and no other dogs. Kids over 14 only.

Polly is an adorable staffordshire, American bulldog. She is approximately 5-6 years old. She came to us after being found as a stray. She was in pretty bad shape with skin issues and a variety of other issues caused by years of neglect. She has spend months in one of our foster homes and is now ready for adoption.

Polly is a sweet girl with people. She is affectionate and calm in the home. She loves suckling on blankets. Polly loves to go for walks and is learning not to pull on the leash.

Polly is not good with other dogs and can be reactive to them on leash. An experienced handler will be able to manage her well but she is strong and you will need some physical strength to handle her. She is not suitable for a home with cats or young kids.

Polly still needs a special diet to control her skin issues, which are mainly caused by allergies to certain foods. Polly's physical build is powerful and she is a bit bow-legged.

She is a wonderful girl who deserves a great life after the years of neglect she has suffered. We hope to find Polly her very own special person who will love her just as she is.

Polly is vaccinated, chipped and spayed. Her adoption fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at matisse1600@gmail.com
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Rudolph
Estimated Breed : Retriever Mix
Approximate Age: 3 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 47 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Rudolph is a super sweet and loving guy with all people and has not yet met someone he hasn't liked. He loves attention and is willing to please. His personality is pretty laid back and gentle and he has a pretty low energy level. Rudolph is not great with other dogs, so he would need to be your one and only. An apartment is not an option for him. Rudolph needs some leash work and is very strong. If you are looking for a guy that just wants to be with you then Rudolph is your guy!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description: Titus is a 3-5 year old bully breed mix who weighs about 65lbs. His owner had a baby and unfortunately no longer had time for him or his sister. He got along well with the baby. He loves to have his head rubbed and go on walks. He is an absolute sweetheart who gets along welll with everyone he meets - he LOVES affection and is so happy when a staff member is able to give him some one on one time. Titus also loves toys! He is housebroken and knows commands. Titus gets along great with his sibling Luna, but has not really liked other dogs here at the shelter. His previous owner said he gets along well with other dogs, but he has been selective about his K9 friends here so far. He is mostly scared of cats and could live in a home with them. He is heartworm positive (not contagious to other dogs) and will recieve treatment for this at our shelter. He is neutered, up to date on vaccinations and microchipped. If you think Titus could be a good fit for your family, please call us at (985) 809-0183 to ask more questions or schedule a private adoption meeting in one of our meet and greet rooms. YES you can bring your dogs to meet him, YES you can adopt if you live out of state although you must come in person so Titus and our staff can meet you. His adoption fee is $65. animal.description:
All dogs listed as on HOLD are NOT available for viewing by the public, unless you are their owner. 
Once a dog is no longer on HOLD, it is able to be viewed by the public, participate in meet & greets, and be adopted!

Adoption cost per dog is $99.00 (puppies under 6 months of age are $150.00). The adoption fee includes the following: OH license good for this calendar year, DA2PP, Bordetella vaccine, Heartworm testing, dewormer, and spay/neuter.  Flea treatment will be provided if fleas are noticed.  All dogs will be spayed/neutered and microchipped before leaving the facility.  An e-collar may be purchased for $15.00.  Because most of our dogs were picked up as strays, we have no knowledge of any behavior or health issues.  Stray dogs are held for 72 hours so that the owners have a chance to redeem them. After that time they are vetted and placed up for adoption. We welcome and encourage the cross posting of our dog's pictures to increase adoptions.

animal.description:
Zuko (zoo-koh) is a 5-year-old pitty mix. He's a big beefcake, weighing about 65lb. He's the perfect dog for someone looking for a lowkey, funny snuggle bug. He is is house and crate trained, walks fine on a leash, and gets along well with humans and dogs. He was adopted from the humane society at 8 weeks old and has lived a comfortable suburban life! Big Zuk is about as easy-going as they come, he gets along with everyone he meets and is pretty happy doing whatever his family is up to! He will go for long walks and run around at the dog park but he also loves to snuggle and won't mind relaxing on the couch all day watching Netflix. Zuko is a bit of a nervous guy. He's rather shy and doesn't love stormy weather. He will do best in a home with someone who can help to comfort him when he is feeling nervous and help to boost his confidence. Zuko is fine with children and other pets and has no social issues whatsoever. When it comes down to it, Zuko is a big lovable goof who will bring lots of smiles and laughs to his forever home. Zuko was in a home with Nala and they were surrendered together.

Nala is a sweet and spicy 8-year-old boxer mix, she is medium-sized and weighs about 55lb. She is house and crate trained, walks fine on a leash, and gets along well with humans and dogs. If you are looking for a life long snuggle buddy with a heart of gold, Nala is your girl! She was adopted from the humane society when she was about 1 year old and has won the hearts of everyone she's met ever since! Nala has lots of energy and loves to run around outside and go on adventures, but she is also a big snuggle bug and loves to cuddle on the couch with her family. She will get about as close as she can to you before curling up into a ball and settling in for a long nap. She has never lived in a home with children, but she gets along great with all humans. Nala has lived in a multiple dog home for her entire life and would love to have some four-legged friends to play with, but she is just fine on her own as well. She has struggled with "happy tail" and would do best in a home where she would not need to be crated, as this is what aggravates her skin the most. She is also very vocal and makes low rumbling noises when she is excited or looking for attention. This could be perceived as aggressive, but she truly doesn't have an aggressive bone in her body and that is just her way of saying "hello!" Nala was in a home with Zuko and they were surrendered together.

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

Meet Blossom! We like to call her "Awesome Blossom." She whelped 10 healthy puppies and is now ready to find her own fur-ever home. Blossom is a smart and energetic girl. If you are looking for a pup to go on adventures with and then come back for a snuggle...she is your girl. She is just a puppy herself at around 1-2 years old. She picks up quick on tricks, but is still working on learning her manners. Blossom will do best with lots of enrichment, dog park visits, and/or doggie daycare to help with her energy and training. Adoption Fee: $225.00
Neoma is a female Terrier/Heeler mix.

I am an excitable puppy but can be nervous with people in new situation. If given the proper time I adjust quickly and will seek out attention.

I am recommended with children 8+, pending observed interaction. I should match with another dog pending meet and greet. I may chase cats, but trainable using a slow positive introduction. Having a fenced in yard would be helpful with that training.

I may require a physically fenced in yard pending your previous experience, location, and other plans for containment. I am not a fit for an apartment.

Before applying to adopt, please do research on both of my breeds characteristics. I could be great with many families but may have more energy than many bargains for.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at debbied@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Oden

Estimated Breed : Staffordshire Terrier Mix

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: approx. 56 lbs

Currently Living at: Boarding

Adoption Fee: $300

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Oden is a big baby that loves affection. He seems to think he is a lap dog since he adores cuddling! Oden gets along well with other dogs. He is strong but obedient. Due to his size and activity level, Oden is recommended for a family with older kids. Oden is hoping one special family will ask about him and give him a loving forever home.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

This special old fellow is approx 10 years old, neutered, vaccinated, crate trained, microchipped, house-trained and ready to give you all that he has.

He is friendly, laid back and walks great on a leash. He gets along fine with other dogs and has no experience with cats. He loves people and fuzzy dog toys. He weighs approx 60# and is believed to be an American Bully / French Bulldog mix.

It is possible that Chance has cancer which will limit his time.. He is hoping to find someone that will share the last part of his journey and help him create a beautiful ending.

animal.description:
I'm so sweet!Snowball was born around January 7, 2017, and weighs about 12 pounds. Snowball was surrender to us by people who have surrendered several dogs in the past. Snowball is an absolute love bug! He does wonderfully with other dogs and doesn't mind cats. Snowball rides beautifully in the car and walks ok on a leash. He is fine with children and should fit into just about any home. We do want to mention that we are working on house training and he is doing well but you may have more work to do in that department if you choose to adopt this amazing guy. Here is an update from his foster mom: I am so happy to be fostering Snowball.He is just a precious 8 lb love bug.He's a little guy with a big, wonderful personality.He loves everyone he meets,including dogs and greets them with hugs and kisses. Snowball loves to play with his toys and will frequently try to carry 2-3 in his little mouth at a time! He needs them all!He likes to play fetch with a ball too.Bringing the ball back, but not really wanting to let it go but then will so I can throw it again and he can chase it. When he is done playing he loves to snuggle and have his belly rubbed.And he will sleep in bed right next to you also.All night.He will follow you around the house to keep you company, but will also lay down for a little nap so you can get chores done.He is not loud and barky.We have a fenced yard but I take him outside on a leash because he is so tiny and he does good on it. Walking very nicely.He pees every time we go outside but is not completely house trained yet.He goes nicely into his crate when I have to go out, but I am also allowing him to be in the gated kitchen for short periods of time when i am gone and he does well. There has been no inappropriate chewing.He rides happily in the car, but wasn't happy getting a bath! When the treats come out he is so cute trying to be the best at sitting. Snowball is going to make someone's family very, very happy. The Adoption Fee for this dog is $650.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Meet Tojo... This handsome guy was surrendered to us when his elderly owners could no longer care for him. He’s a 12 year old mini poodle. Tojo is overweight at 35 lbs and will be put on a diet in his foster home. Tojo is a super sweet little guy. A total gentleman and people pup. He loves to be with his people at all times. He’s been an only dog his whole life. He’s adjusting well to all the dogs in his foster home and does great he just doesn’t like them in his face and will give a warning to that. Tojo is house trained. He does have meds for his thyroid which is also contributes to him being overweight. He also has meds for anxiety. Tojo would be the perfect companion for a laid back household. He will be fully utd, hw tested and altered before placement. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter! Puppies will be altered before adoption. All rescues and shelters practice pediatric spay and neuter. This is essential in our rescue efforts and it is a policy that we will stick by. All dogs over 8 weeks and 2 pounds will be altered before adoption. There are no exceptions to this rule on all healthy and adoptable dogs. 

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

ADOPTION APPLICATION

We are a foster home based rescue organization. **Only approved adopters can meet our dogs** 

If you are interested in adopting please follow these instructions before contacting Rescue4All. Virtually all of your questions will be answered by following these instructions: 

1. Go to our website www.rescue4all.org

If you’re interested in potentially adopting one of our megaesophagus dogs you must fully research the genetic disease, understand what it is, and how to manage it.

**Please WATCH the videos on our FB page about Megaesophagus 
https://www.facebook.com/pg/rescue4all/videos/?ref=page_internal

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Kiona aka Kiki is 11 months old mixed breed female with mild megaesophagus.

She is so pretty and unbelievably social and sweet. 

She is happy, great with other dogs, great with cats, and is hilarious. 

She loves to grab a toy and talk to you with her Roo-Roos while it’s in her mouth. 

She is house trained, crate trained, spayed, and fully vaccinated.

Her megaesophagus is very well managed and and pretty mild. 

She, like all our megaesophagus dogs, eats a raw diet of turkey ad The Honest Kitchen (fruit and veggie premix) in her Bailey chair. She stays vertical for 20-30 min and rarely regurgitates.

She is a completely normal, healthy, active puppy who just happens to need to eat a little different. ?

animal.description:
Beautiful brindled Cheza is an approximately 3 year old, 55-pound Pitbull/Boxer/Cattle Dog mix who has not been treated well by humans in the past. Her foster reports that she can be a spastic love bug, but will need an experienced dog owner who is willing to help her continue to build her trust of other people.

Smart and eager to please, Cheza is a fast learner and already knows the commands for sit, stay, lay down, paw, and kiss. She also knows “who’s that,” which is a training tool to help her deal with her fear of strangers on walks. She is housebroken as long as she remains on her schedule. Cheza will get excited and run to the door if she needs to go outside. Her crate is her safe space and she does well when left alone in it, sleeping in the crate overnight and napping in an area close to her person during the day. Cheza even eats her meals in her crate as that is where she feels safest. While Cheza can be fearful of people, she is great with other dogs and respects her foster's old Chihuahua and her two pocket Pitties who aren’t very sure of her. Due to a strong prey drive, cats are not a good idea.

If she has bones and toys to chew on, she will leave human stuff alone. If she does not have toys she will make her own toys from human stuff (blankets being her personal favorite). She loves to explore her foster's fenced yard; she enjoys fetch and is very good at it. As a bonus, Cheza will keep pesky squirrels out of your yard. While she likes walks, Cheza's "stranger danger" tendencies can lead to reactive pulling, growling, and barking if she is really fearful — hence her need for an experienced adopter who is willing to work with her. A freedom harness has proven to be a valuable tool for walks. She does very well in the car and enjoys the ride. 

Cheza needs a single family home of dog-savvy adults with a 6-foot privacy fence. The fewer new people she sees, the less stressed she is. Cheza is the best of both worlds — she will play fetch and have zoomies in the yard but will be a total love bug in the house. Her new family will be richly rewarded with devotion!

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description:
MURFREESBORO, TENNESSEE

Meet Kimber!  She is a beautiful young female Anatolian Shepherd Dog.  Kimber's DOB is estimated to be December 2019 so she just turned a year old.

Kimber's family had a critical illness in the family and was no longer able to care for her.  Kimber gave birth to a litter of puppies in October, right after she came into foster care with us and she is just now getting to the point where she will soon be ready for adoption.   She still needs to be spayed  but she will be ready for a new home very soon.

Kimber is a very sweet and friendly girl.  She is good with other dogs and is also good with children.  

Kimber is housebroken and knows some basic commands.  She is still very much a puppy, herself, and will benefit greatly from obedience classes.

Transport: **PLEASE READ CAREFULLY**

If you are within 1,000 miles, we can usually help with transport using volunteer drivers (depending on the route/availability of volunteers).

If you live farther than 1,000 miles, we can still assist, however, the adopting party will need to drive any mileage over 1,000 miles.

For example, if you live 1200 miles away, you would have to drive 200 miles out.

Not sure how far away you are? Please ask google, she will tell you!

Licorice is so sweet, loves to snuggle and run around in the yard. He has a kink in his tail and an adorable little underbite. He is happy and loves to be around people. Dislikes, the cold weather. Licorice is about 3 months old and 15 lbs now.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Licorice is the right pup for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

NOTE: Most puppies do best in the company of an older dog who can teach them "doggy manners," so homes with at least one other dog usually will be given preference in puppy adoptions. Please read Suzanne Clothier's wonderful article, "It Takes a Pack to Raise a Puppy!"

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US! We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us atAlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption. animal.description: HUGO is not in the shelter; he is in a foster home in our Rescue Program, so use the contact info at the bottom of his description. Hugo is an approx 1 year old neutered male Mastiff mix who would love to be your new best friend! Hugo is super sweet and loves attention. He has a slight bone defect of his skull that gives him a bit of a wobbly gait, and causes his tongue to hang out rather adorably. Hugo has had an MRI and been evaluated by a neurologist who feels Hugo's condition is stable and does not require intervention. Hugo is in a foster home with two rabbits and has done well with a cat he met. He basically loves everyone he meets, including other dogs. Because of Hugo's condition, he cannot always stop himself once he gets going. As his foster mom put it - 'when he plays he cannonballs his body in to people, pets and things like a reckless barrel of joy' - so Hugo will do well with a fenced yard where he can burn off energy, and a home without tight spaces. While Hugo would love a canince playmate, because he does not have good control of his movements, care will need to be taken in choosing his friends as not all dogs will appreciate having their space invaded. He is a large but compact 94 pounds. Hugo's front paws tend to turn under when he walks, so he should be walked mainly on grass or other soft surfaces. Hugo is a joy to be around and will be a wonderful companion for the right person or family! He has been neutered, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested, and microchipped. Please contact AdoptADog@animal-advocates.org or 410 880 2488 option 3.

I am a 3 year old Heeler mix and is approximately 62 pounds. Her foster mom says she is a very loving, cuddly girl who loves attention. Ginger would do best in a home that has lots of room to run around and play. She  loves to play with her toys and chew on hard bones that smell good. If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. animal.description:
I was saying to myself just this morning, "Rhett," I said, "Rhett, you know what you need? You need a person all your own." So I sat down to write my bio for the nice people here at the Potter League, because apparently that's the kind of thing they do - find nice people for extremely intelligent and lovable, slightly goofy, playful and remarkably handsome dogs who are...I shudder to type this...couchless. That's right: I have no couch to call my own. Could you be persuaded to volunteer yours?

All kidding aside, Rhett is one happy and playful dude. His tail never stops wagging and he is hoping to land himself in home that will include both lots of adventures and lots of snuggly couch time for naps. Older kids? Rhett says bring 'em on! He is an outgoing guy who just loves every person he meets and will flourish in a home where he can shine as your ONLY pet. 

He can't wait to meet you, so fill out an application at www.potterleague.org and then give our Animal Care & Adoption Center a call at 401-846-8276 to set up an appointment today.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Online Adoption Application
Bentley is about 35 lbs, low rider. He was dumped in a NY Kill shelter. He is shy at first but warms up once he gets comfortable. He needs someone that can give him patience and approach him slowly until he gets to know them. He is good with other dogs and is okay with cats too. He will need some time to adjust in a home as he does have some fear issues.

Bentley has some quirks and we have hired a trainer, so his adopter will need to follow and continue with his training. He feel he should be in an adult only home based on his fear.

Bentley was rescued from Staten Island AC, he did have some fear aggression issues when we took him in. He is a corgi pit mix, and with his foster home he is wonderful. We hired a trainer where he stayed for over a month. He has learned commands and does not show fear aggression with us anymore, but he needs an experienced adopter who will continue to work with him, and when going into a new home he will need to overcome his fear again. His trainer can work with the adopter, phone calls, zoom, whatever and will always help throughout his whole life. We have a list of commands for Bentley that we want the new adopter to work with him so he does not forget what he has learned. We do not want Bentley to fail. In his foster home Bentley is housebroken, loving, and good with other dogs but does need time to get to know the other dogs. He is good with cats also. Initially it takes him time to get to know bigger dogs as he may be a little fearful with them in the beginning. But his foster home has 10 dogs big and small and he is good with all of them and the Cats too. He is very good in a crate, and lots of his commands revolve around the crate. He loves being walked and going out in the yard. Bentley is up to date on shots, neutered and microchipped. He loves snuggling with his person on the couch and is well behaved when left alone. He deserved to be saved, and he deserves a home that will love and give him the time to overcome his fears.

Soyer 'Max' Ferdinand is an approximately 1.5 year old lab that weighs 67 pounds.  Max is a very sweet and loving, good natured boy that does great with other dogs and is fine with cats.  He is very playful and enjoys chasing balls, belly rubs, walks, and LOVES to play tug.  Max has good leash manners and does know some basic commands but could use continued work and training which will be an easy task given his motivation for treats.  Max is still very young and does have his bouts of playful, mischievous energy but with regular exercise he settles down quickly.  He is house trained and crate trained but doesn particulary enjoy the crate.  He gets a bit of separation anxiety so he will do best in a home where his humans are home more than gone.

Soyer 'Max' Ferdinand is up to date on shots and preventatives and is microchipped.   His adoption fee is $250 plus any additional donation you feel appropriate.  Our adoption fee is set to a level to make adoptions happen.  They do not cover our costs. Thank you for your generosity and interest in our dogs!   

All dogs adopted locally through SGDR receive a free six-week session of obedience classes and a lifetime of behavior support through our Project REWARD program with trainer Charlotte Blake.

You must have an approved application before being able to visit a dog. Visit our website below for an adoption application https://www.snootygiggles.com/dog-application/

If you expect to leave the dog alone for long periods of time, please do not consider adopting a puppy.  Puppies need lots of attention and companionship.  Thanks.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

animal.description:
Hi I’m Darby! I’m a one year old, 41lb, black lab mix. I’m an energetic pup with lots of love to give. I want to love everyone, humans, dogs and cats. My foster sister cat doesn’t want to play with me though. She tries to avoid me whenever I want to play. Sometimes I think it’s because I still haven’t realized how big I am. I have two favorite things. My first favorite is toys. I will chew apart any toy you put in front of me. My foster mom is glad that I only chew toys and not anything in the house. My second favorite thing is hills!!! Yes, hills! I have to stop and look at every hill I walk past. I always want to run up and down them. Speaking of walks, I walk really well on a leash. I stay pretty close unless I stop to sniff something. I also take my time to go to the bathroom. But make sure I go before we go back inside! I’m notorious for not going to the bathroom on a walk and wanting to go out again after. I’m pretty good at pawing at the door to let you know I have to go, but sometimes I’m not so good at telling you in time. A regular potty schedule helps me not have any accidents! I’m excited to find a furever family who will run, play, cuddle and love me.

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Elizabeth, but some call me Lizzie. I'm a sweet and loving 3 year old, 53lb lab mix looking for a place to call my forever home. 
I spent most of my life as an outdoor dog in the South, so it's taking me a while to get used to the good life of a house pet. I'm a little bit skittish and nervous around sudden movements and loud or weird noises, but I get better and better every day. 
I'm working on learning to go outside to do my business and to get in my kennel nicely. Like I said, I didn't live in a house before so all of this is pretty new to me. But I'm a smart girl and I know I can quickly learn if I'm guided gently and taught what to do. I'm already getting a lot better! I'm also not a huge barker and I love to destroy fluffy toys. I like to run around and play, but I also enjoy relaxing next to my person at night after I got some exercise.
I love walks! I walk nicely and pull very little, mostly just when something startles me. I think that'll get better as I get used to the hustle and bustle of the city and realize that I'm safe with my person by my side.
My foster parents believe that I will do best in a home that is relatively quiet, with not a lot of people coming in and out and with no small children since they can be a little unpredictable and that's a little scary for me. This might all get better in the future, but right now I need to ease into all of these new experiences. I like dogs that are nice and chill! Right now I live with a girl dog that's a couple years older than me and I like to follow her around and follow her lead. She makes me feel safe. My ideal home would have another dog that is confident, gentle, and laid back so I can learn from them.
I know that not everyone might be up for loving a dog that requires a little bit more patience and a gentle guiding hand, but if you open up your heart and your home to me, get ready... because I have soo much love and loyalty to give! You will become my whole world!

animal.description: Please contact Laura (laura@pawsandprayers.org) for more information about this pet. My name is Biscuit and my favorite pastime is peeing on any tree or bush that looks like it needs it. I can't help myself. Don't judge me. I like what I like. Other things I like is having my head rubbed, snuggling on the couch with you and taking a nice walk. Oh and I do love my sweater! You see, I went undercover for a while and you couldn't recognize me. My coat made me look like I could be on the welcome to Jamaica poster. I had dreadlocks all over-even coming from my ears! My behind hurt because it didn't have the regular maintenance I needed. I constantly ran in circles trying to help it but I couldn't reach it. This was very frustrating. I was kept in a garage away from the family I knew. I was jealous of the new baby they had and I wasn't being treated like their baby anymore. I was sad, frustrated, alone and in pain. My foster mom didn't like this so she whisked me away to a doctor who gave me my much overdue vaccines and a wonderful spa day. I feel SO much better now that you can tell what I am! I'm a 30lb Spaniel and am about 6yrs old. I like to meet new people and say hello but can tend to change my mind after a few minutes and growl. I need them to think that I can protect myself even though I'm small. I've just been through so much and it will take a few weeks for me to fully trust you. I'm not good with kids because, hey, I just don't like sharing with those loud and crazy acting mini people. I live with 4 large foster brothers and sisters. They made me nervous at first because they're HUGE compared to me so I just steered clear of them. After my spa day, I wasn't tired at all! I felt so amazing that I decided to start seeing what this toy box was about that all these dogs thought was so great. I grabbed the biggest bone I could find so everyone knew how bad to the bone I really am. I think I fooled them. I even acted like I may be interested in playing with the smallest one but the whole crew came my way and I ducked out. Don't get me wrong, I am now running with the pack all day but they just get so crazy when they play. I'd prefer a home with no children and not too much chaos. I'm middle aged and don't have time for drama or craziness anymore. I'd rather spend my time getting love. I can get growly from time to time if you're rubbing near my butt. Sometimes I seem to like the booty scratch but sometimes I just don't. When you hear me growl, please stop what you're doing. This is the only way I can tell you I don't like it. I was also nicked on my ear by some groomer lady who was hurrying with me and I now really hate grooming appointments. This is a necessity for me but I will need muzzled and possibly a pill to help me not want to groom her fingers! If you think you have everything I need, then put an application in and email my foster mom. She is busy trying to keep up with making me feel loved. Thanks for reading my story. She actually says I'm a very easy houseguest. I go into my crate with ease but would prefer someone who is home more than not. My adoption fee is $300 which includes my neuter, vaccines, microchip and heartworm, flea and tick prevention.

Male Lab/Husky mix

It’s me Ruger! (Or Ruge, or Rugey-baby). I am now super confident in my foster home. I am FINALLY starting to play with toys, I can roam the house freely even when my foster parents leave. I was panicking in my crate so they decided to trust me, and I proved them right. I spent most of the time lounging on the couch, chewing on a bone and sleeping while they were gone. #bigboy

With my newfound confidence, I also like to pull on the leash now. It’s a work in progress they say, but I’m just soooo excited to see the world outside the backyard that I just want to go, go, go. Aside from the leash thing I am still a perfectly sweet boy. I like to chase my foster sister around the backyard, chase the bunnies out, and I’m starting to work on fetch too!

FENCED YARD 100% required 

We would recommend that he be adopted into a home with another playful dog his size and everything level.

Not eligible to be only dog in home 

NO APARTMENTS  

Interested in adopting me?

animal.description: Meet Kermit!! No he is not the green guy but he is a beautiful big white Shepherd mix who is looking for an active family where he can try to be a lap dog. Kermit was transferred into us from a rescue partner if northern ND where he did spend some time in a foster home. In that home he lived with a female dog that he did well with and since coming to the shelter he has found some other canine friends as well. He has been in to meet a few kitties and was good but has never lived with them so we can never guarantee behaviors in the home. Kermit is working on his basic manners (he is trying hard not to jump)and does well on leash walks. He keeps his kennel tidy and has proven to be accident free in a home. His perfect day would be some playtime with a friend in the yard and some night time cuddles on the couch. Please apply on our website to get pre-approved and to set up an appointment to meet Kermit. https://www.humanesocietyotc.org/adopt

animal.description:
Rogan's zest for life is as big as his smile (which is pretty stinking big when he's having a good time)! While a little hand-shy and hesitant with new people, once he's comfortable around you, you can pretty much fold him up, wrestle him, flip him over for belly rubs, and he loves all of it. He's got personality for miles and has a definite zest for life - he balances play with snuggles and sometimes mixes them both together in zoomies that end full-speed in your lap where he'll curl into you while chewing on his toy. He also has a bubbly enthusiasm for other dogs - he enjoys watching them from afar but also loves to play with them in the yard. He is an adorable little watermelon and you're going to wish you could just nibble on because he's that stinking cute! Rogan is around 5 years old and weighs 44 lbs.

Visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to set up a meet!
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

DIETRICH - ID#A045033
Hi! My name is DIETRICH. I am a neutered male, white and tricolor Jack (Parson) Russell Terrier mix. The shelter staff think I am about 2 years and 2 months old. I have been at the shelter since Oct 17, 2020.

I LOVE TO: hang out with my favorite people. I am a really loving dog once I get to know you.
I HAVE: a very active personality. I love to run around and play in the yard!
I GET ALONG WELL WITH: most other dogs.
I WOULD RATHER NOT: live with children. I am a quiet dog and would be scared in a very active household.
I NEED: a dog experienced family.
I AM: a sweet dog and would be a great addition to a calm household, possibly with other dogs as well!

STARTING THE ADOPTION PROCESS:

Thank you for your interest in adopting an animal. To begin the process you will need to access & submit an adoption application. 

You can access our adoption application at either PetProjectFoundation.org or on the City of San Clemente’s website, under the Animal Services option.  
An adoption application can be submitted to the shelter, via Fax at (949) 366-4765, via email to Animalservices@scdpanimalshelter.org, or dropped off at the shelter in the drop box, located by our front door.  The San Clemente – Dana Point Animal Shelter is located at 221 Avenida Fabricante in San Clemente.

We look forward to receiving your application and will be in contact with you via email.

The shelter is currently closed to walk-in public, due to the COVID-19 virus. 

Staff are on site during our regular business hours (below), to address phone calls,  offer shelter services by appointment only, as well as handle any/all animal control concerns.

Our regular business hours are as follows:  
Monday – Closed
Tuesday – 10-4
Wednesday – 10-4
Thursday – 10-4
Friday – 10-4
Saturday – 10-4
Sunday – 12-3
 
In person services are by appointment only, due to the COVID-19 virus, please contact the shelter at (949) 492-1617, for more information.

animal.description:
If you're looking for someone to light up your world, Spark is sure to be your guy! He is a model passenger in the car, loves to catch snackies you toss to him, and has a fun loving personality once he gets to know you. 

His simple pleasure are: 
- Fetch 
- Snackies 
- Couch time 

He'll even dance in circles when he is excited about any of these things. He is such a sweet little companion. 

He has a kind, gentle soul and enjoys snuggling up with a soft blanket on the couch. He likes to chew on his tennis ball and dog toys, but he'll occasionally grab one to use as a pillow. Not only does he love chewing on tennis balls, he's a rockstar when it comes to playing fetch. All in all, Spark is a sweet and trusting dog that would make a great companion. Between his naps, he'll come up and rest his head on you for pets and snuggles. He's a perfect balance of wanting to be by your side and content doing his own thing (which usually entails finding the perfect napping spot).

So, if you're looking for a balance between couch buddy and walking partner, reach out to the CASPCA today!


 Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: White Weight: 37.5lbs Age: 10yrs 5mths 0wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
I was rescued a few months ago by a young woman who didn’t realize how much energy I have! She gave me up because she couldn’t give me the exercise and training I need, and said I should really belong to someone with a fenced in yard where I can run around and play. I have a very sweet personality and love to cuddle with my humans, but I have been through a lot of change, so I sometimes get scared in new or unknown situations. The humans call this “fear reactivity.” I have been in training to work on my behavior, but I still need someone who can spend time working with me on my reactivity and confidence, and give me lots of exercise and love! I am happiest zooming around outside, I love to play in puddles, and I am great at learning new tricks! Once I am comfortable in my new home, I will make a super loyal and loving companion.

If you are interested in meeting this pooch, please download the Adoption Questionnaire (farescue.org/pdf_files/questionnaire_canine.pdf), fill it out and email it back to us at info@farescue.org or fax (310) 362-0321. You can also meet this and/or other available dogs at our weekend adoptions.

[Zadie is 2 years old and weighs 50 lbs.]

___________

Daisy is an adorable little chihuahua/whippet mix around 4 years old and 10 pounds. This tiny girl is very sweet, but like many dogs her size she can be skittish when it comes to the big world around her.  We will require a home with a secure, fenced yard for Daisy. A nice quiet home without children would be best.  She does like other dogs (who can play appropriately for her size) and her foster believes that she would be indifferent with cats. 

It has taken Daisy some time to be comfortable in her foster home, so we expect that she will need a patient adopter who will give her time to get comfortable. That's when her inner goofball comes out and she likes to play!  As you can see, she is very photogenic and has her Snapchat game on point. :-)

Daisy is mostly housetrained but still has some accidents and nervous/excited urination. That may resolve itself when she gets home in a routine and feels secure. Her foster mom said she is a very special little girl and we are excited to be part of her journey and look forward to heling her find her people!

Daisy is spayed, microchipped, vaccinated and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.  Our $300 adoption fee helps to cover these expenses.

animal.description:
Meet our rescued dog Stephan. Stephan is completely blind, but he is an intelligent, cheerful, active boy. He is 5 years old, 50lb,21.5 inch tall. Stephan East Siberian Laika  . We do not know what happened in his life until 2019, but we assume Stephan lived with an irresponsible owner who did not feed him, did not heal and did not love. Our volunteers found him in early spring 2019. Poor baby boy, he was running completely bling with a torn rope around his neck, bewildered, frightened and worn out. When was called he is run up to the volunteers and ask-“Take me with you”. He jump into the car without any problems, and at that moment Stephan began a new life. Volunteer took Stephan to doctor and doctor give a conclusion, dog was absolutely bling. The doctor advised to remove the eyeballs because there was internal pressure caused severe pain. Blindness does not prevent Stephan from being a cheerful, super active, kind, affectionate boy. He is human oriented. Stephan is looking his family forever. He wants to be at home and is ready to learn everything that will be taught to him. He is quick-witted and quick to teach. 
Stephan knows the leashes, but at first when you go out into the street he can pull, as many active dogs do in anticipation of the street and active walks. While Stephan is getting used to the his human and hem home,he cannot be released from the lash, as he can run away for the squirrels and birds. Stephan can dominate with boy dogs but friends with girls dogs. Stephan is not at all aggressive. When he is not familiar with the premises, he may be afraid of the stairs,then the fear goes away. Stephan can guard his food since he has been starving for a long time. Active,loves to walk, run, play. Despite the absence of eyes,Stephan quickly gets used to the new environment. He is very happy when to receive attention. At the such moments, Stephan freezes and enjoys communicating with a human. He is guided by sounds a human’s voice, smell and memory. If there is an unexpected loud sound, then it may be frightened, afraid of fireworks.  If you give our special boy a home love affection  care,then you will find a devoted friend, companion protector)) Ideally, we are considering a family with a strong young active owner. The boy Stephan-Stanley needs space, so he will fit into house with a large yard with a closed fence. If you are seriously interested in our special needs boy Stephan-Stanley please write to the Dire Straits Paws rescue group email: dsprescue@gmail..com. email the organizer: j72pechorina@gmail.com or write to the phone number: 347-530-7069 Request application form we will send you free.

animal.description:
Dog Name: Anderson

Sex: Neutered Male

Breed: Black lab mix

Age: Estimated about 8 years

Weight: 63 lbs

Medical Needs: Heartworm +, will receive treatment 2/8 and 2/9 at 9:40 through Grass Roots Rescue. It will consist of getting an injection 2 days in a row, followed by 30 days of keeping him calm/limiting activity. He'll also get blood work that day as we are keeping an eye on his kidney function

Housebroken: Yes. He doesn't alert you to go out, so keeping him a schedule is best

Crate trained: Yes. Toss a treat in he will go in with no problem. He's quiet while he's in there.

Good in the car: Yes. He will initially try to be up front with you, but takes correction well and will just chill in the back once you set the boundary.

Good on a leash: He's a bit "hot out of the gate" bc he gets real excited to be walked, but less than a minute later he just trots along with minimal/no pulling.

Energy level: Medium

Need a fenced in yard: No

Dog Friendly: Yes

If yes, does your foster need another dog in its adoptive home? No.

Cat Friendly? The shelter he was at previously said yes; current foster does not have cats

Kid Friendly: Unsure, but likely

If yes, what's the youngest child you'd recommend they be placed with? 10 and up due to size and sharp teeth. He's not an incessant jumper, but will jump if excited. He's also likely lived outside most of his life and had to eat whatever was available. As a result, he's missing some teeth and his bottom canines are filed to a VERY sharp point. He's NOT any type of aggressive, but giving treats can be tricky as it's easy to scratch your hand on his tooth in the exchange. He's a good catcher, so we've been throwing them to him during training instead of hand feeding.

Special traits that make your foster special or that we need to know about them?

Anderson is an all around great dog. He's a very friendly, happy boy. He seeks out attention and pets, and loves to be around people. He's shown minimal interest in toys and hasn't been destructive of household items. As previously mentioned, he's likely been an outside dog most his life. He will need continued basic boundary work (get your head out of the trash can, keep your nose away from the oven), but takes direction very well. He understands "no" and will stop when told. He's very food motivated, and has already learned to sit on command. He pays attention to his handlers and looks for instruction. He wants to be a lap dog so badly; he'll lay on top of you if you'll let him. He makes a fantastic weighted blanket
