animal.description:
Chanel is a 15lb 6 year old chihuahua.
She will follow you from room to room, curious about what you are doing.  She will lay on a pile of blankets next to you on the couch, or on the opposite side of the couch, she is not really a "lap" dog, but stays close.
She shows no signs of aggression unless her personal space is invaded by a younger more playful pup.  She doesn't prefer a house with younger, playful dogs, but will do well as an only dog or with an older dog that isn't intrusive into her personal space.
She does exceptionally well around our 5 year old son, as she was raised with kids in her original home.
She is overweight, but she does really well on a leash, so if she is walked regularly she should slim down to a healthier weight.
She is set to be spayed and microchipped and have some dental work done on 1/22.She will be ready for adoption 1/24..
Adoption fee $400




All UnderDogs are spayed/neutered, heartworm checked, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and heartworm/flea/tick preventatives.  For consideration for one or more dogs, we require that an on-line application is filled out.  

TO ADOPT THIS DOG PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AT https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/. 

Sorry, we do not adopt outside of Florida.  Applicants are subject to a home visit, and veterinary references will be checked. Please include a vet reference (including phone number) when applying online.

Our application process:
FIRST, an application must be approved for adoption from our rescue.
SECOND, we determine whether the dog that has been applied for is a "good match" for the household that wants to adopt him/her.  We take into consideration the dog's activity level, compatibility with other members of the household (human and other pets), etc.
If your application has been approved, but the dog you applied for is no longer available, please take the time and look over our adoptable dogs again.  We will make every effort to find the right dog for an approved applicant.

We hope you agree and understand that our goal to find the best forever home is our #1 priority! Please fill out an Adoption Application at https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/

animal.description:
This cute little dude is Kubota, he is about 8 weeks old and weighs about 10lbs.  He came here with his mom and sister.  His mom is a Shepherd mix and he looks like she might have some Lab and Shepherd in him.  They were rescued from a backyard in Texas where mama was tied to a tree and had to have her puppies under the tree.  A neighbor called animal control and they were taken to the local shelter.  We were asked to take them in and find them homes.  Kubota is a fun guy, he absolutely loves to play.  He can also be a big snuggle bug.  He would love to find a home that has room for him to play!!  Kubota is currently being fostered in Cheyenne, Wyoming.  He absolutely loves being in Wyoming and is ready to find his new home.  If you would like to meet Kubota please fill out an application at
   
www.lowridersofthewest.org

Kubota’s adoption fee is $375.00  - if you have any questions please email the rescue with them.

animal.description:
Gravity is a six-month-old 36lb cattle dog mix! He was found with a broken back at six weeks old, which was surgically repaired, but he also incurred a deep laceration to his spinal cord. This has left him partially paralyzed from the lower back down. There is a chance that some of the nerves will regenerate over the next two years,but it's important to note that any progress will be slow and steady. Although he is partially paralyzed he gets around great and absolutely loves playing with dogs of all sizes in ages and going for a nice long walks. He's an active puppy and loves to go for car rides & beach romps but also loves keeping himself entertained basking in a sunny spot in the house with a chew toy. 

Check him out on Facebook at 'Gravity, a puppy's journey' and Instagram at 'defyinggravitypup'.


Medical Needs:
 - Incontinence: Gravity is incontinent both urinary & fecal. He needs to be manually expressed multiple times a day (at the most every two hours up to every 4 to 5 hours) it takes a bit of patience to learn but besides getting a bit of an arm workout it's fairly easy, promise! Typically when you express him, he'll pee & poop so it makes it easier to plan your day. ***On a day to day basis Gravity wears belly bands so he doesn't pee everywhere and uses diapers for certain situations like car rides if I need to stop in a store (he gets worked up if alone), at PT and at my shop while I'm out walking dogs.
 - Gut health: He's currently eating Purina Pro Plan complete essentials which has a probiotic. He's on 2 supplements- one for fiber to keep things flowing and a cranberry chew to help keep UTIs away. He also gets a spoonful of yogurt added to each meal.
 - Paw care: It's important to keep his front nails short for gripping and his back paws protected. Because he drags but flips them I to the right position he whittles away at those nails. To keep them safe on long walks we use PAWZ booties (size medium)

Behavioral needs:
 - Separation Anxiety: Gravity has displayed some pretty significant separation anxiety since he has been in Massachusetts. It is in his best interest that he goes to home with at least one other dog as it definitely makes him more confident. He can be left uncrated and unsupervised with my dog at this point and he is totally fine. If he is at my shop alone while I am out walking, even with other people in the store-he will bark and whine but go through periods of time where he'll be able to settle. If I leave him alone, even for something as brief as picking up a to-go coffee order he can get himself pretty worked up and will be panting by the time I get back to the car. Sometimes he gets himself so worked up in these various situations that he will poop himself. These are the scenarios I will make sure he's in a diaper for . He is crated for each of his meals and every time I go outside for brief things like getting the mail or putting out the trash, and he is now totally settled. He is doing better in a crate for longer stints when the crate is covered with the lights off & music playing, but if somethings startles him he will start crying and typically then takes him a while to settle.
 - Barking: When he plays he loves to use his voice! He also barks when left alone.

Financial needs:
 - Physical Therapy: Gravity is currently enrolled in physical therapy twice a week at Boston Animal Hospital. It is important that he remains seeing his team to regain some flexion of his knees and his overall balance and strength. Physical therapy can be quite costly so it's important to note that we see PT in his future indefinitely
 - Daily supplies: Belly bands, diapers, pee mats, supplements, food, yogurt, booties etc

Fun things to know about Gravity:
 - Likes: Loves dogs of all sizes & ages, obsessed with Benebones and chew toys and loves a good stuffy to shred, loves long walks, beach time is his favorite, great for car rides, we're working on leash skills and he walks wonderfully in a pack
 - Dislikes: Being left completely alone, vacuum cleaners, steam cleaners, random scary loud noises


Name: Gravity
Breed: Cattle Dog Mix
Sex: Male
Age: 6 months
Weight: 36
Spayed/Neutered: Not yet
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Unknown - brief interactions were promising however he's still a pup (mouthy) and has never lived with kids
Good with Dogs: Yes! Loves all dogs
Good with Cats: Unknown



IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.


Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.


At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.




NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If interested in any of our animals for adoption, or to foster an animal, please fill out the respective application here to get the process started. Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.
Hi! I'm Kodiak, a sweet, affectionate boy who is super excited to find my forever home. I was rescued from a construction site near a rail yard and I am thrilled to have an opportunity to find a family that I can love.

Training and trust will be key to make sure I can be the best dog I can be. I'm house trained, crate trained and get so excited when I see my leash but could use a little help learning not so pull so much.

I love as much attention as possible, laying around and tugging on my rope toy. I would prefer not to share my home with any other animals or small children. I was a stray and need some time to learn my surroundings. A home where I can continue to learn will make me most happy.

I've been described as gorgeous, affectionate, smart and strong. I am very alert when it comes to loud noises, such as the garbage truck or new sounds. My future owners will need to be patient and kind, and continue with my training and socialization.

I'm a sweet boy who is longing for a home where I'll never be left behind again. Can you help me complete my journey and make my dreams of a loving home come true?

For more information or questions, email atrembley@yahoo.com.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Zoie! I am the sweetest girl ever, and don't want to share you with anyone else. I don't want any other dogs or kids in the house to have to share your attention with. I love car rides and am the perfect passenger. My previous owners say I can escape any crate, but my foster lets me free roam inside when they're gone and I am very trustworthy to not chew or destroy the house. I get so excited on walks that I pull sometimes, but I just need someone to show me how to be a proper lady. I get nervous in new places or if there is a lot of commotion, but who can blame me?

Zoie is about 4.5 years old, spayed, UTD on her vaccines, and house trained. Zoie is a very sweet, gentle girl. She likes toys and chewing on them. We are still learning about her personality, but she will take some time to fully decompress. 

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org or speak directly to her adoption counselor, Kaeli, at kaeli@madrescueinc.org

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Meet Clancy! Clancy is part of a group of puppies rescued after having been born in a ravine behind a VA Hospital in rural Georgia. We have been told that there has been a feral colony of dogs living in that area for the past few years. Given this information and having not seen any of the adults in the area, we really cant give any guesses on breed or adult size unfortunately. 

 

These puppies are adorably cute and fluffy but they are full of spunk! Having grown up in the cold woods, these pups need a confident medium to large size dog to teach them how to be loved family members in a home. While they are learning their manners, we think it is best they not be in homes with young children - ages 10 and up only please. 

 

Interested in adding some spunky fun to your life? Email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

animal.description:
Meet Waylon! He is an 11-month-old husky mix who was adopted from us as a puppy. Unfortunately, recently he was not doing well with the families 7-year-old daughter. Waylon is an awesome dog; he is great with other dogs and good with kids 10 and above. He is super sweet and just loves to be with his people. 

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an online application at rescuerowinc.org 
*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours. 
*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we require a homecheck
*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):
 Dogs 10 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee 
 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee
_____________________________________________________________________
Rescue Row is a section 501(c)3 (non-profit) no-kill all volunteer dog rescue organization, incorporated in March 2017, serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances.
We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. 
Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. 

Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs. 
Rescue Row stands ready to help you, the prospective adopter or foster home, find a companion who will thrive in your home. We are here to assist you in every way possible throughout the adoption process and will continue to be a helpful resource after you have welcomed your new pets into your life.

animal.description:
A SENIOR DOG THAT SAVED HIS FAMILY IS NOW LOOKING FOR SOMEONE TO SAVE HIS LIFE!

Kesshie and his brother were sleeping in their previous home when suddenly they smelled smoke. They immediately ran into the bedroom of their former owners and started barking loudly, letting them know that something was wrong. The family woke up and followed them down the stairs and outside to safely. By the time emergency services arrived, the home was already engulfed in flames; had it not been for Kesshie and his brother, the family may not have been so lucky. The family was so very grateful for their dogs, but worry soon followed...the former family home was no longer habitable. Left without shelter, the family was forced to move-in with relatives, but unfortunately, Kesshie and his brother were not able to join them and were forced to be surrendered to a high-kill shelter. Being that Kesshie's brother was young, he was quick to be adopted but sadly, Kesshie was left behind and continued to be passed over (presumably only because of his age). Kesshie is glad his former family is now safe; but now it is his turn to rediscover what the safety of home and family feels like! 

Kesshie is a young (but still vibrant and friendly) 10 years of age. He weighs approximately 42lbs, is neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped and heartworm negative. Kesshie loves people of all sizes and gets along well with other dogs (cats are not known). 

If you have an open place in your heart and home, won't you please consider giving this sweet senior boy all of the love and creature comforts provided by a permanent home? Please complete an application to meet Kesshie today!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

Hi, my name is Bree! I am a strong, clumsy, lovable four-year-old dog who is looking for my forever family. My foster mom always tells me how sweet and adorable I am and that there is a perfect home out there for me here in Colorado. I may be a little shy at first but I am quick to warm up when you give me the time and patience to adjust to new places, people, and situations. My foster family says I am silly, and I love my toys and dog bed. I am crate trained and potty trained and I love to go on walks. My furry foster sisters have helped me be more confident out in the world. We play chase, tug-of-war, and run around the yard together. I am good with other dogs and with children. Please consider opening your hearts and home to me and I will forever be your friend.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

AdoptaGSD.org

Please consider that some of these dogs have been abandoned or ignored by their previous owners, having little interaction with someone who cares about them.

When adopted, they will need time to adjust to the changes in their life.

Hi, my name is Ruby and I'm a beautiful one year old GSD who was surrendered to FRGSR by my former senior owner after I knocked her down and caused her to be injured to the point where she could no longer care for me. I didn't mean to hurt her - I just have a good bit of puppy energy that was too much for her. Sadly, I have some medical issues of my own. My pastern (lower left leg) angles out to the side, possibly due to a growth plate injury, and because this issue wasn't addressed during my puppy months, it looks like I'm going to require an extensive surgery to help me regain proper use of my leg. I am able to run and play now, but this issue does need to be corrected. FRGSR is consulting with an orthopedic specialist regarding next steps and the hope is to find an adopter who will commit to my aftercare, which will require leash-only exercise for approximately three months. I'm a happy, somewhat shy dog who's hoping there's someone out there waiting just for me! Is that you? If you are interested, please go to adoptagsd.org and submit an online application.

Although we do our best to keep our adoptable animals page as current as possible,the animals you see may already be in an adoption process.

animal.description:
PLEASE DIRECT INQUIRIES ABOUT ADOPTABLE DOGS TO OUR FACEBOOK. WE ARE CURRENTLY UNABLE TO PROCESS APPLICATIONS VIA EMAIL DUE TO LIMITED STAFF. OUR CONTACT IS THROUGH FACEBOOK MESSENGER. https://www.facebook.com/REDRescueEveryDog/

Meet Fancy! Fancy is a super sweet Pomeranian who is estimated to be 6-8 years old and 6-8lbs. Once comfortable with you she loves being held and babied, but can be evasive about being picked up, especially with new people. She is a favorite with volunteers she knows and trusts, as she is a kind and happy soul without a mean bone in her body. As sweet and kind as Fancy is, she is also an enormous flight risk who loses all recall once out of her safe area. She is tiny and can (and has) slipped out under feet through doors and gates. Fancy is most comfortable in her routine,
home environment. She is not comfortable in new places or situations and can easily slip out of collars and harnesses, so a home that wants to take her out on walks is not a match to her. Once she is out and loose she is nearly impossible for a team to catch and would be impossible for a single person. Due to this she a double barrier catch system is required for her adoptive home.  She has been good for grooming with us. She does well with other like sized and kind dogs and with a quiet and consistent routine is quiet and joyous. Again, this dog requires a fully fenced and secure yard with a visible fence, as well as a sturdy, high quality crate. She is a flight risk if she gets loose, so a safe routine for going out and a yard like Fort Knox is required. She also had been debarked before we rescued her, and so you will need a vet that understands this and will need to be willing to do any dentals without tubing. She has a slight case of alopecia that has been getting better and growing hair back since she was spayed. She is an exceptionally sweet dog, looking for  a loyal and loving family to finally give her the home she has always deserved. Adoption donation is $600.

THIS DOG IS IN FOSTER CARE IN POULSBO, WA. MEET AND GREETS WILL TAKE PLACE THERE AS WELL. 

REQUIREMENTS FOR ADOPTION:

- Incredibly secure, visibly fenced yard 
- Double barrier catch system 
- Sturdy/safe crate space
- Vet & groomer references (Or ability to groom on your own).

ADOPTION PROCESS: 

If you are interested in adoption please fill out an application here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php
Answers to the application MUST be sent via message on Facebook (we do not receive applications sent via email)

1. Once the application is received it will be reviewed by that animals caseworker. 

2. If your application is seen as a good fit to the pet you are applying for we will request photos of your fenced yard as well as your current crate or the crate you plan on purchasing. 

3. Once received we will schedule a phone interview with you to discuss the pet and the next steps, should a match be seen.  

4. Meet and greet/adoption 

PLEASE, CONSIDER SPONSORING THIS COMPANION ANIMAL IN NEED. R.E.D. RELIES ON DONATIONS TO SAVE, SUPPORT AND OFTEN REHABILITATE LIVES. WHICH BRINGS LIVES LIKE THIS TO THE FINAL GOAL OF PROVIDING A SAFE PATH TO A NEW FOREVER HOME. GO TO SPONSOR BUTTON TO HELP SAVE A LIFE! FOR MORE INFORMATION ON R.E.D. GO TO WWW.RESCUEEVERYDOG.ORG Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children. Adoption donation for this companion animal is  Donations cover some of the care costs for R.E.D. animals. Like housing, supportive care, medical needs and food. All R.E.D. animals are spayed or neutered and vaccinated. Most are micro chipped with adopter registration included. R.E.D. is a 501 C3 and all donations support our life saving missions. For more information and to complete the on line adoption application on R.E.D., please, see our website at www.rescueeverydog.org. 
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE FOLLOWING TO APPLY TO ADOPT: Not all applicants will be approved for requested animals. R.E.D. reserves the right to refuse service and adoption without explanation. R.E.D. is the companion animal's advocate and will select the most suitably matched home/environment for the the companion animals emotional needs and management requirements based on each companion animal's breed(s) general needs and the unique needs of each individual animal in our care. R.E.D. requires all applicants and adopters to conduct themselves in a respectful and courteous manner. R.E.D. updates it animals adoption postings daily. If you wish to apply to adopt this companion animal go to the on line application at R.E.D.'s website www.rescueeverydog.org. and look under adoption. Before applying, please, read the following information. 
(1) Application, Phone interview, Home visit are required. Adoption Donations are generally $350 and above (please refer to dogs posted bio). Donations support R.E.D.'s life saving missions and medical and other care given.(2) R.E.D. Dogs are spayed or neutered prior to adoption, vaccinated for Parvo Distemper and generally are micro chipped. (3) You must be at least 18 years of age to complete the application or to apply to adopt a companion animal. For the safety of children and dogs and limited information on dog the dogs interaction with children- R.E.D generally prefers/requires children in adoptive home to be approximately 5 or 6 years of age and up unless otherwise noted in the dog profile. All children must be behavior appropriate with animals. (4) R.E.D. does not a ship animals to out of state adopters. Out of state adopters must come to meet the animal in person in Washington if approved for a meet and greet with a R.E.D. companion animal. Thank you.

animal.description:
*Please read the whole bio. As Annie needs a special adopter*

Annie is a sweet special maltipoo girl with a little "sass". Big dog personality in a small body. She is 6 years old and 9.5 lbs. She was surrendered to the rescue when her previous owner could not care for her anymore. She wants to be with her people all the time if she can, we call her the little velcro dog =) Annie is not potty trained and she does mark (hike her leg) inside the house. We are working hard on that but for now she is wearing a diaper inside. She can be without diaper for a short period if monitored. Annie reminds me of typical dog that was never properly socialized and she can get a little nervous/growly around new dogs. She is currently living with two large dogs in the house. She does not like cats. She eats separately in her crate due to food guarding. Annie sometimes gets nervous when pushed beyond her comfort zone and that can make her a little snappy. Due to this, she would do best in a calmer household with no younger children. Annie loves her daily walks and doesn’t mind riding in the car. She loves to go where I go. Annie potentially has allergies and she is on a trial run on Apoquel tabs to help with her itchy-ness. Interested in Annie? Next step would be to fill out an application, link below.

Annie is heartworm negative, spayed and up-to-date on vaccinations. The dog has a microchip that will be transferred to the adopter upon completion of the adoption process. The adoption fee is $300. 

If you would like to meet Annie or have any questions, you can email the foster home at malinsavland@gmail.com

Ready to adopt?  Please complete our on line application here:
https://pethoodga.org/dog-adoption-request/
It will be reviewed and the foster will contact you.

To sponsor a dog, please visit pethoodga.org/give

animal.description:
Tucker was found living under a car at a local automotive plant. He was terrified of people. After eventually being lured out with food, after he'd been starved for days, he was taken to animal control.  Tucker reverted back to a very fearful state. 

After months of rehabilitation with volunteers, Tucker has become comfortable enough to interact with volunteers and even newly introduced stranges. He has proven himself to be a sweet, goofy and playful boy.

He has a clear aversion to leashes, which volunteers are working with him to overcome.

He is food motivated, eager to please and we are confident that he will be a fantastic companion.

We are looking for a REGISTERED RESCUE with the experience to take over his rehabilitation. Proof of professional training experience and veterinary reference a must in this case. 

Tucker is a unique case for our shelter. 
*****************************************************************************************************
Interested in adopting?

Due to COVID- 19 the shelter is closed to the public at this time.

We are still conducting adoptions, but with a few changes. :)

1. Submit an application through our website at wacshelter.com if you are interested in giving one of our shelter animals a home

2. We will schedule phone interviews once the online application has been processed.

3. If the animal applied for is determined to be a good fit for the home, we will schedule a controlled in person meeting with the cat or dog prior to the adoption.

*ADOPTION FEE:

$95 (cash only) and includes:

Spay/neuter
First vaccines
FIV/FeLV test (cats)
Heartworm test (dogs)
Rabies vaccine (if old enough).

*****************************************************************************************************
Additional questions?

Does this dog get along with cats? There is almost always an acclimation period when a new pet joins the household. We are happy to suggest a few ways to ease the transition. A new dog should never be left alone with resident pets though.

Does this dog respond well to other dogs? No dog loves every other dog. A proper introduction (meet and greet) would be required as part of the application process.

Is this dog good with children? The better question is how the children have been taught to handle animals. A dog will respond negatively if he/she is not being handled properly. We can offer suggestions on how to teach children to interact with dogs and pay attention to body language. Young children should never be left unsupervised with new animals.

*****************************************************************************************************
Want to help a real shelter animal by adopting a Mini Plush Pet from our limited time fundraiser? Check out our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/wacshelter/ for details!

Surrendered for marking indoors and anxiety when left alone. ----- Additional Notes: Kiko has been a blast to have a round. We crate when we are not home and he is working on crate training so anxiety is not an an issue for us. He may be a barker for an apartment if he hears people and other sounds. But here, he is good. He loves to play with the other dogs and is just a happy little guy. We don't really know breeds for sure but were told boston/rat but I see some corgi and chi characteristics. My guess would be that he is a heinz 57! -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- If interested in meeting and potentially adopting, please read the adoption requirements and complete the adoption application located at forbellessake.org. Once processed and approved a meet and greet can be scheduled and if a match an adoption can be finalized at that time. FBS standard adoption fee is $175. All residents are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, dewormed, microchipped, and treated for any known medical needs. Breeds are best guess. Housetraining is not guaranteed but crate training is worked on with all residents. A secure physically fenced yard is required. See Less

Calling all the senior dogs lovers!  You must meet Oreo Cookies.  She is 10+ old boxer mix about 60 lb.  She is as sweet as can be and loves everyone that she meets.  She spends most of the days lounging and going on short walks.  Due to her age, she sufferers from arthritis but she has been on pain medications and seems to be comfortable.  Ideally, she should be living in a house without many stairs.  She also unfortunately she is HW positive so she is waiting for its treatment to complete.  Currently she is 1st stage of treatments and waiting for injections. Her trial adopter needs to be able to take her to a vet in Towson at least twice for it. She really is a doll and looking for someone who would spend her golden years. CHN will be responsible for her dental and HW treatment. 

Adoption Fee is $150
She is up to date on vaccines and has had a wellness exam, heartworm tested and micro-chipped.

Applications are required before meeting a dog. To fill out an application go to

IF THE DOG IS ON PETFINDER IT IS STILL AVAILABLE

Nike
8 yo male
Fawn Sugar Face
50 pounds
Kid Friendly
Slow Intro Cat Friendly
Small Dog Friendly
Leash Trained
Okay in Crate
Prefers to not be left behind
fostered in Forks, Wa

Hi! I am Nike and I LOVE people!!! I am good with cats after proper introduction
and have 2 who take naps with me on my bed now. My foster mom says to not
let my age fool you. I still have plenty of wiggles that need daily exercise. I prefer
to be where my human is at and will move rooms to be near my humans. I like
car rides. I don't like the crate but if you insist on it, I will stay quietly in one when I am not able to go in the car with you. I am a bit of a mischief maker when left out loose so to let me ride along, right?

My foster mom says my ideal home means I get to be with my
human(s) nearly 100% of the time. I am a senior and want as much time as possible to love on my peeps and being alone is for the birds, not me. I walk well on a leash and also enjoy a good zoomies session when I am off leash.
I haven't met other dogs much, although the neighbor dachshunds were coolio. The few I have met thru a fence on walks I am polite to and a pal might be something I wouldn't mind. My foster mom says I am not a barker or a licker but that I do love hugs and lots of loving from my humans.

Does Nike sound like a match for your family?
Consider applying to adopt today at:

https://www.nwboxerrescue.org/adoption-form

If you would like to adopt him, fill out an adoption application on our website www.nwboxerrescue.org

Like us on facebook for more photos of this handsome boy, as well as other boxers we have available! www.facebook.com/northwestboxerrescue

animal.description:
We would love Opal and Ray Ray to be adopted as a bonded pair. However, we would certainly consider separating them for the right situation. Please read their beautiful heart felt bio below.

Like a lot of great people and animals, Opal and Ray Ray came from humble beginnings. Only they know all of the details of their past, but Opal came to ACT from a hoarding situation and Ray Ray came to ACT as a young dog with multiple issues including an infected eye that had to be removed. Their luck turned when they both found their way to a loving foster home that offered good food, a quiet, consistent environment and a loving person all their own. Of course, they soon became "foster fails and were adopted by their foster mother. Life was very, very good, until their person suddenly passed away, and they found themselves back at ACT. Their world turned upside down and they clung to each other, the only thing they knew. 
Opal is a survivor and makes lemonade out of lemons whenever possible. She would love a new home with soft beds, both human and dog, lots of lap time, and lots of walks where she can stretch out on the grass and smell the roses. She wants love and knows how to get it. Ray Ray, on the other hand, lacks Opal's confidence. Generally afraid of new things, Ray Ray would do well in a quiet home where he could come or retreat as needed. But once he feels at home, you can bring out Ray Ray's magic wand...... Cheetos!!! Wave a Cheeto at Ray Ray and you'll be amazed at how many commands he knows.... provided a Cheeto is in sight. 
If dogs reminisce, I think they miss their human. We all do. But life is for the living, and both Opal and Ray Ray have a lot of life left to live. Opal and Ray Ray have a few special needs, but they have a lot of love to give.

Gorgeous FALCON is a 1 year old 45 lb. German short haired pointer mix looking for his furever home. This handsome boy is a gentle soul who loves to run and play in the yard, then nap on the sofa. He is a bit timid and requires the companionship of a confident, friendly dog to help him navigate the world. He is housebroken, crate trained and dog and cat friendly. We check vet references before we contact applicants. If you would like to meet Falcon, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at
dreamhouserescue.org.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

animal.description:
Here is Hobbes' story...
We got him about six years ago from Animal Control, he was a stray. He was very fearful and timid, but with a lot of work and love from our volunteers, he overcame these issues.
He was adopted to a great home, but it was an apartment, and Hobbes did some damage to the carpeting and walls when his mom left to go to work. Second home was better, he had a fenced yard and another dog for company. Those people had to move and their new house did not have an adequate fence to keep him in. We tried to help them improve their fence but Hobbes still escaped.
So he's back here, thank goodness, safe and sound. Hobbes must have a 6' high, solid wooden fence. He can climb chain link like a monkey. The second family that had him said he had occasional seizures, although we have not witnessed any. He is a nice dog, kind of quirky personality (you need to meet him to appreciate it) and is a great companion. Okay with dogs and older (10 years +) kids. Most likely would chase cats.All of our dogs are available for a $200 donation. This includes them being spayed/neutered, micro-chipped, and fully vaccinated.
To adopt a dog, we require an approved pre-application, as well as a securely fenced yard. This means an actual, physical, fence. 'Invisible' fences are not acceptable, sorry. If you live in an apartment and do not have a yard, we are not able to adopt to you.
Please contact us at: dogtownmutts@gmail.com for details.
Please note: we typically do not do 'out of the area' adoptions. This would be any location more than 60 miles away from the Reno/Carson City area. 1/31/21 8:46 PM

animal.description:
Hagrid is a very charming 1 year old St. Bernard weighing 160 lbs and growing.  He is a very sensitive young man  He enjoys the company of other dogs at the dog park and, because he is very curious about other dogs, he sometimes forgets his training when he sees them on walks.  He’s a little leery of strangers he meets on a walk…until he has the opportunity to learn that they can be trusted.
Hagrid likes stuffed toys with squeakers in them, which he will use to tell you all about it. He loves to snuggle and enjoys leather couches to keep cool through the night.  
He is not crate trained but is fine being left alone in the house…he may, however, chew on a shoe of his favorite person if left alone with the available shoe...he misses his human so much!   Hagrid needs a home with a fenced yard (not invisible/electric fence) and a person or family that does not need to leave him alone regularly for long hours.  He has lived with 2 other dogs, so might enjoy a doggy companion in his forever home.  And while he has not lived with cats, he has enjoyed the ones he met. (Hagrid is currently unneutered; adopter will be required, under monitored contract, to neuter him by a specific date.)
(A $400 adoption fee is required.) 
If you are interested in this dog, please go to the Adopt page of our website where you will find a link to an adoption application form  https://www.chewdogrescue.org/index.php/component/rsform/form/5-adoption-application-form
 
If you have previously submitted an application form, there is no need to re-apply. Just let us know you're interested in this dog. We do our best to match families and dogs so everyone is pleased and the placement is permanent. We reserve the right to refuse an applicant if the home situation is incompatible with the needs of the rescue dog. Rescue is about doing our best for the dog. We do home and reference checks.  All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and are up to date with current vaccinations, before being placed in their forever homes.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED! We are always looking for good foster homes. Our rescue is foster based and we can always save more dogs if we have foster homes for them to go into. It is not a long term commitment. We have been able to find good forever homes in a short time. We also welcome volunteers who can help transport dogs and help with our outreach and fund raising efforts. Please contact us if you can help.

MEET ROSIE – 3 year female. Rosie was surrendered to a shelter in Tennessee when her owners no longer wanted her. It took a few weeks, but Rosie finally arrived at Recycled Rotts on Saturday, Jan. 9th. She is such a good girl, but still not quite sure what is going on. Rosie can be very timid and shy when you first meet, but it doesn't take her long to warm up. A treat is definitely a friend maker, and a piece of cheese will really bring out the wag in her rottie tail. Rosie is good with other dogs, and loved spending the evening with her new friend, Behr. We do not know how she will react to small dogs or cats.  She is housebroken, but it might take a week or so to get into a new routine. Crates are ok for a while, but she would prefer to be near her people. Rosie would love to have a new family to call her own. One that will make her feel special, let her know she is loved. If there are children in the family we prefer they are over the age of 7.

If you are interested in including Rosie in your home, please go to our website http://www.recycledrotts.org/wp/?page_id=150 for the rescue location, placement policies, placement fee and the link to our online application.

Max is a 2 yo male Hound/Pointer Mix and weighs approx 40 lbs. He is a sweetheart and craves love and attention from people. He is very smart and eager to please, but he gets a little anxious and nervous at times trying to anticipate what is being asked of him. He has passed 6 weeks of training at Kai's Academy in Ankeny but he needs continued training and reinforcement of the things he has learned. He needs an owner that is willing take the time he needs to learn the expectations in the his new home and give him a predictable schedule to help with his fears of the unknown. He is working on kennel training and leash training in his foster home. He is very strong and loves to go for walks but can pull quite hard at times. The proper harness, training collar, and practice will help with this. Max gets along with other dogs and enjoys meeting new dogs, but needs a home with children over 10 or no children. He is not currently in a foster home with cats, but he has been exposed to them and does well with them.

If you are interested in meeting Max, please complete an online application at https://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.duplie.com/forms/196/dog-application

animal.description: Say hello to Dakota! She is a 4-year-old, intelligent, Siberian Husky mix looking for a family who loves and appreciates the typical husky shenanigans. She is a husky who likes to have fun and can find it in everything she does. She's a smart girl that already knows sit, shake, and down. She's a great car rider and loves to feel the wind in her face. Be sure to keep an eye on this smart girl as she has rolled the electric window down before and tried to exit the vehicle while moving. Dakota is social and friendly girl and loves to go places to meet new people. She even enjoys visits to the groomer and the vet. Dakota likes to play with other dogs her own size, but prefers to be left on her own when chewing on a bone and eating her meals. No small dogs, small animals, or cats for her though, as they look like fun play things and sometimes prey. Dakota is hoping for a family that understands life with a husky and all the things that come with that. She is also hoping her family likes to be active and spend time with her. She's a bit overweight and could use some help shedding those extra pounds. She LOVES to go swimming. If she sees a lake or pond she will jump right in. She is crate trained in that she won't mess in her crate but it's not her favorite place to be. She would rather be left out loose during the day and in her old home she would behave while her owner was at work. Dakota was only returned to us because her owner's job changed and required a lot of travel. She is house trained and would be sure to hold it when left alone. Just be sure to have the trash out of reach and don't leave any food on the counters, not even a loaf of bread. Dakota likes the older kids and wants to snuggle with them. No apartments for her. Dakota's adoption fee is $150. If you would like to adopt Dakota go to www.pawpatroldayton.com/adopt and fill out an application. All of our animals are vaccinated, micro-chipped and spayed/neutered before being adopted.

animal.description:
Sweet, cuddly, affectionate, easy-going, laid back - sound like your dream dog? Then you simply must meet our sweet lovebug, Patches! Around 3 years old and 70 lbs, she could use to shed a few extra pounds, but hey, who among us couldn't?! It's just more of her to love! And let us tell you, this girl LOVES love. She is a velcro dog for sure. Working from home? Need some moral support? Patches will be Team You all day everyday. Sitting by your side and making it all seem effortless. Patches is a mature gal who knows how to respect nice things and surely knows where to do her business. Personal space, not so much her thing, as the closer she can get to you the better and she is sure to be an awesome foot warmer as you sit at the desk, television or kitchen table. She is your all around best mate! Cuddles and food may tie as her favorite things. If Patches sounds like she may be on your list of favorite things then submit an application to come to meet her today! A dog this sweet surely won't be hanging around the farm long!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
**Please read Annie Rae's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!**

Meet elegant Annie Rae, an 8-year old, 48-pound, Red Bone Coonhound lady.

Annie was found straying alone.  She had clearly been away from care for a long time since she was way underweight.  Now that she’s in a loving foster home, she is making up for lost meals, feasting on as much food as the vet thinks is healthy and begging for more.

Annie is a mature girl with a teenage spirit.  She’s very outgoing and curious about everything.  She wants to meet every new person that comes to her foster home and she follows every scent she picks up all around the house and the yard. 

Annie Rae is very good on a leash and loves her long walks just as much as she loves coming back home and cuddling up and sleep next to nice warm human friend.
-- 
All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  

To adopt or learn more about Annie Rae, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $425]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
Say hello to Bruce, the king of zoomies! This 5-year-old Pittie might be a meaty 76 pounds, but don't let that fool you -- he’s still as agile and speedy as can be! And even though he might look quite serious, he’s a goofy guy who will play all day if you let him. Tug of war with his favorite rope toy = pure bliss in Bruce’s book. Bruce knows basic obedience and engages well during training, but he can sometimes forget how big he is and would therefore do best in a home without small children who he could easy knock over. He's also crate and potty trained and does very well in his crate. Bruce is very friendly with women, but he tends to take a little longer to warm up to men and prefers interactions to be on his terms until he’s comfortable. He's fostered with dogs of all sizes and ages, as well as dog-savvy cats, and he’d really love another playful dog who he can zoom around and play tug with. If Bruce sounds like the meaty man of your dreams, then apply today! His adoption fee is $250.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!
